{"title_page": "Tyne and Wear Metro", "text_new": "{{short description|Rapid-transit rail network in north-east England}}\n{{redirect|Newcastle Metro|the light rail system in Newcastle, Australia|Newcastle Light Rail}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox public transit\n| box_width = 340px\n| name = Tyne and Wear Metro\n| image = Tyne Wear Metro logo.svg\n| imagesize = 70px\n| image2 = 4057 at Monument Metro station, Newcastle, 20 June 2015 (crop).jpg\n| imagesize2 = 300px\n| caption2 = A [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocar]] at [[Monument Metro station|Monument]], branded in the current black and yellow corporate livery.\n| image3 = Tyne & Wear Metro diagram.png\n| imagesize3 = 300px\n| caption3 = A schematic map of the Tyne and Wear Metro network.\n| locale = [[Tyne and Wear]]\n| transit_type = {{plainlist|\n* [[Light rail]]\n* [[Rapid transit]]\n}}\n| lines = [[#Routes and services|2]]\n| stations = [[List of Tyne and Wear Metro stations|60]]\n| annual_ridership = 36.4 million (2018/19)<ref name=\"2018/19DfTstats\">{{cite web |title=Light Rail and Tram Statistics, England: 2018/19 |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/809894/light-rail-and-tram-statistics-england-2019.pdf |publisher=[[Department for Transport]] |access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref><br>{{increase}} 0.1%\n| headquarters = Station Road<br>[[Gosforth]]<br>[[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n| began_operation = 11 August 1980<br>({{Years or months ago|1980|8}})\n| owner = [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|Nexus]]\n| operator = Nexus\n| chief_executive = \n| vehicles = 89 [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]]\n| train_length = {{cvt|27.81|m|ftin}}\n| system_length = {{cvt|77.5|km|mi}}<ref name=\"TAGBI\"/>\n| track_gauge = {{RailGauge|sg|al=on}}\n| el = [[Overhead line]]<br>(1,500 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]])\n| minimum_radius_of_curvature = \n| top_speed = {{cvt|80|kph|mph}}\n| map_name = \n| map = \n| map_state = \n| website = https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| area served = {{plainlist|\n* [[Gateshead]]\n* [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n* [[North Tyneside]]\n* [[South Tyneside]]\n* [[Sunderland]]\n}}\n| line_number = \n| start = \n| end = \n| character = \n}}\n{{Tyne and Wear Metro}}\n\nThe '''Tyne and Wear Metro''' is a [[light rail]] network linking [[South Tyneside]] and [[Sunderland]] with [[Gateshead]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[North Tyneside]] and [[Newcastle International Airport|Newcastle Airport]]. The network opened in stages from August 1980, and now serves a total of 60 stations, with two lines covering {{convert|48.2|mi|km|abbr=}} of track.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://trl.co.uk/reports/CR357|title=The longer term effects of the Tyne and Wear Metro|last=Davoudi|first=S.|last2=Gillard|first2=A.|date=1 January 1993|website=TRL|publisher=|isbn=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=30 June 2018|last3=Healey|first3=P.|last4=Pullen|first4=B.|last5=Raybould|first5=S.|last6=Robinson|first6=F.|last7=Silcock|first7=D.|last8=Usher|first8=D.|last9=Wymer|first9=C.}}</ref><ref name=\"railwaytechnology\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/tyne/|title=Tyne & Wear Metro Rapid Transit System, United Kingdom|last=|first=|date=|website=Railway Technology|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TTstations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/stations/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Stations|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"TAGBI\" /> \n\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro has been described as the \"first modern light rail system in the [[United Kingdom]]\".<ref name=\"Metrobuilt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/history/how-metro-was-built|title=How Metro was built|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 April 2015}}</ref> In 2018\u201319, an estimated 36.4 million passenger journeys were made on the Metro, making it the third-most used [[tram]] and [[light rail]] network in the [[United Kingdom]], after [[London]]'s [[Docklands Light Railway]] (121.8 million passenger journeys) and the [[Manchester Metrolink]] (43.7 million passenger journeys).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/809894/light-rail-and-tram-statistics-england-2019.pdf|title=Light rail and tram statistics, England: 2018/19|last=|first=|date=19 June 2019|website=Department for Transport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe initial Tyne and Wear Metro network opened between August 1980 and March 1984, mostly using converted former railway lines, linked with new tunnel infrastructure. Further extensions to the original network were opened in November 1991 (from [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]] to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]]),<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metros-airport-extension-celebrates-its-25th-year|title=Metro's airport extension celebrates its 25th year|last=|first=|date=17 November 2016|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> and March 2002 (from [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] to [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]] and [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]]).<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/1905281.stm|title=Metro system extended to Sunderland|date=2002-04-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-18|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe system is [[#Ownership and operators|owned and operated]] by [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|Nexus]], having been formerly operated under contract by [[DB Regio]] from 2010 until April 2017, with Nexus taking over direct operation of the system, under public ownership.<ref name=\"Conend\">{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-35800733|title=Tyne and Wear Metro operator contract to end in 2017|date=14 March 2016|work=BBC News|accessdate=20 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Metpublic\">{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-39466348|title=Tyne and Wear Metro to be publicly run by Nexus|date=1 April 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=3 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Predecessor===\n{{main|Tyneside Electrics}}\nThe present system uses much former railway infrastructure, mostly constructed between 1834 and 1882, one of the oldest parts being the [[Newcastle & North Shields Railway|Newcastle and North Shields Railway]], which opened in 1839. In 1904, in response to [[Newcastle Corporation Tramways|tramway competition]] which was taking away passengers, the [[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]] started [[railway electrification in Great Britain|electrifying]] parts of their local railway network north of the [[River Tyne]] with a 600\u00a0[[Volt|V]] [[direct current|DC]] [[third-rail]] system, forming one of the earliest suburban electric networks, known as the [[Tyneside Electrics|''Tyneside Electrics'']]. In 1938, the line south of the [[River Tyne]] between [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and {{rws|South Shields}} was also electrified.\n\nUnder [[British Rail]] in the 1960s, the decision was made to de-electrify the ''Tyneside Electrics'' network and convert it to diesel operation, owing to falling passenger numbers and the cost of renewing end-of-life electrical infrastructure and rolling stock. The [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] to [[South Shields]] line was de-electrified in 1963, along with the [[North Tyneside]] routes, in 1967.<ref name=\"TAGBI\">{{cite book|last1=Schwandle|first1=Robert|title=Tram Atlas Britain & Ireland|date=|publisher=Robert Schwandl|year=2015|isbn=9783936573459|location=Berlin, Germany|pp=132\u2013137}}</ref><ref name=\"TNEE\">{{cite book|last1=Hoole|first1=K.|title=North Eastern Electrics: The History of the Tyneside Electric Passenger Services, 1904\u201367|date=|publisher=The Oakwood Press|year=1987|isbn=9780853613589|location=United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emus.co.uk/zone/tyneside/tyneside.htm|title=The Tyneside Electrics|last=|first=|date=|website=Suburban Electric Railway Association|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref> This was widely viewed as a backward step, as the [[diesel multiple unit|diesel trains]] were slower than the electric trains they replaced.<ref name=\"SRT23\">{{cite book|last1=Young|first1=Alan|title=Suburban Railways of Tyneside|date=|publisher=Martin Bairstow|year=1999|isbn=9781871944204|location=|page=23|pages=}}</ref>\n\n===Planning and construction===\nIn the early 1970s, the poor local transport system was identified as one of the main factors holding back the region's economy, and in 1971 a study was commissioned by the recently created [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Authority|Tyneside Passenger Transport Authority]] (now known as ''Nexus'') into how the transport system could be improved.\n\nThis study recommended reviving the badly run-down former Tyneside Electrics network by converting it into an electrified [[rapid transit]] system, which would include a new underground section to better serve the busy central areas of [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[Gateshead]], as it was felt that the existing rail network didn't serve these areas adequately. This new system was intended to be the core of a new integrated transport network, with buses acting as feeders to purpose-built transport interchanges. The plans were approved by the Tyneside Metropolitan Railway Bill, which was passed by [[Parliament]] in July 1973. Around 70% of the funding for the scheme came from a central [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] grant, with the remainder coming from local sources.<ref name=\"Nexus-history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/history/landmarks-urban-transport|title=Landmarks in urban transport|last=|first=|date=|year=|website=Nexus|publisher=Nexus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Meet Your Metro|publisher=Tyne and Wear Transport|year=June 1978|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n\nThree railway lines, totalling {{convert|26|mi|km|abbr=}} were to be converted into Metro lines as part of the initial system \u2013 these being the [[North Tyneside Loop]] and [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] to [[South Shields]] branch (both of which were formerly part of the ''Tyneside Electrics'' network), and a short stretch of the freight-only [[Ponteland Railway]] between {{Metro|South Gosforth}} and [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]], which had not seen any passenger traffic since 1929.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" />\n\nThe converted railway lines were to be connected by around {{convert|6|mi|km|abbr=}} of new infrastructure, which was built both to separate the Metro from the existing rail network, and also to create the new underground routes under [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[Gateshead]]. Around {{convert|4|mi|km|abbr=}} of the new infrastructure was in [[#Tunnels|tunnels]], whilst the remainder was either at ground level or elevated. The elevated sections included the [[Queen Elizabeth II Bridge, Newcastle upon Tyne|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge]], a new {{convert|350|m|ft|abbr=on|}} bridge carrying the Metro across the [[River Tyne]], and the {{convert|815|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Byker Viaduct]] across the [[Ouseburn Valley]], between {{Metro|Byker}} and {{Metro|Manors}}.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> \n\nConstruction work began in October 1974. This involved the construction of the new infrastructure, re-electrifying the routes with [[overhead line]] equipment, the upgrading or relocation of existing stations, and the construction of several new stations, some of which were underground. By 1984, the final cost of the project was \u00a3265 million (equivalent to \u00a3{{Inflation|UK|265|1984|r=0|fmt=c}}&nbsp;million in {{CURRENTYEAR}}).<ref name=\"SRT\">{{cite book|last1=Young|first1=Alan|title=Suburban Railways of Tyneside|date=|publisher=Martin Bairstow|year=1999|isbn=9781871944204|location=|pages=90\u201394}}</ref>{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} The Tyne and Wear Metro was the first railway in the [[United Kingdom]] to operate using the [[metric system]], with all speeds and distances stated in [[metric units]] only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcts.org.uk/branches/north_east/page.htm?id=north%20east/metro|title=Guide to Travelling on the Tyne & Wear Metro|last=|first=|date=22 September 2011|website=Railway Correspondance and Travel Society (RCTS)|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> It was also the first transport system in the [[United Kingdom]] to be designed to be fully [[accessibility|accessible]] to passengers with disabilities, with step-free access available at all stations across the network.<ref name=\"CLmetrohistory\" />\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Construction of the Metro\n|width=215 |height=165\n|align=center\n|footer=\n|Haymarket Metro Station escalator shaft (8691421213).jpg|alt1=Tunnel\n |The escalator shaft at [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], under construction in the late 1970s.|Metro Bridge nearing completion, 1978 (25760168724).jpg|alt2=QEII Bridge\n |The [[Queen Elizabeth II Bridge, Newcastle upon Tyne|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge]] over the [[River Tyne]], nearing completion in 1978.|Tyne Dock Metro Station (8691436755).jpg|alt3=Tyne Dock \n |The Metro station at [[Tyne Dock Metro station|Tyne Dock]], under construction in the early 1980s.}}\n\n===Opening===\n\nOriginally, the Tyne and Wear Metro was intended to be opened in stages between 1979 and 1981.<ref name=\":9\" /> The first stages of the original network (between [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]] and [[Tynemouth Metro station|Tynemouth]]) opened in August 1980, with the final stage (between [[Heworth Interchange|Heworth]] and [[South Shields]]) opening in March 1984.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /> The opening dates of services and stations are as follows:<ref name=\"TAGBI\" />\n\n*'''11 August 1980:''' [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]] to [[Tynemouth Metro station|Tynemouth]] via [[Benton Metro station|Benton]]\n*'''10 May 1981:''' [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]] to [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]]\n*'''15 November 1981:''' [[Heworth Interchange|Heworth]] to [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]]\n*'''14 November 1982:''' [[St James Metro station|St. James]] to [[Tynemouth Metro station|Tynemouth]] via [[Wallsend Metro station|Wallsend]]\n*'''24 March 1984:''' [[Heworth Interchange|Heworth]] to [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]]\n*'''15 September 1985:''' [[Kingston Park Metro station|Kingston Park]]\n*'''16 September 1985:''' [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]]\n*'''19 March 1986:''' [[Palmersville Metro station|Palmersville]]\n*'''17 November 1991:''' [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]] to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]]\n*'''31 March 2002:''' [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] to [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]]\n*'''28 April 2002:''' [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane]]\n*'''11 December 2005:''' [[Northumberland Park Metro station|Northumberland Park]]\n*'''17 March 2008:''' [[Simonside Metro station|Simonside]]\n\n===Integration===\nWhen the Tyne and Wear Metro first opened, it was intended to form part of an [[integrated public transport]] system, with the local bus network reconfigured to act as 'feeder' services for the Metro. The Metro was intended to cover trunk journeys, while buses were re-designed towards shorter, local trips, to bring passengers to and from Metro stations, using [[unified ticketing]], and with their timetable integrated with the Metro schedule. Several purpose-built transport interchanges, such as {{metro|Four Lane Ends}}, [[Heworth Interchange|Heworth]] and {{metro|Regent Centre}} were built for this purpose. Integration was short-lived, and lasted until the [[Bus deregulation|deregulation]] of bus services, in 1986.<ref name=\"CLmetrohistory\">{{cite news|last=Meechan|first=Simon|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/history/how-tyne-wear-metro-made-12031209|title=How the Tyne and Wear Metro was made - we go back 36 years to the very beginning|date=16 October 2016|newspaper=ChronicleLive|access-date=15 June 2019|url-status=live|publisher=|location=}}</ref> It is, however, still possible to purchase [[Transfare]] tickets, in order to combine a journey made using multiple modes of transport in Tyne and Wear.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/adult-transfare|title=Adult Transfare|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tyne and Wear and Tees Rail Map.svg|thumb|600px|center|A map of commuter rail services in the region, including Tyne and Wear Metro services.]]\n\n==Expansion and growth==\n\n=== Extension to Newcastle Airport ===\nIn November 1991, the Tyne and Wear Metro was extended to [[Newcastle International Airport|Newcastle Airport]] \u2013 at a cost of \u00a312 million.<ref name=\":7\" /> The new section of track, covering a distance of around {{convert|2.2|mi|km|abbr=}}, continued along the alignment of the former [[Ponteland Railway]], with two purpose-built stations constructed at [[Callerton Parkway Metro station|Callerton Parkway]] and [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]].<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /><ref name=\"LRTAHLR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lrta.org/mrthistory.html|title=The History of Tramways and Evolution of Light Rail|last=|first=|date=|website=Light Rail Transit Association|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Extension to Wearside ===\nIn March 2002, a \u00a3100&nbsp;million extension, covering {{convert|11.5|mi|km|abbr=}}, was opened from {{metro|Pelaw}} to [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]] and {{metro|South Hylton}}.<ref name=\":8\" /> The extension used part of the existing [[Durham Coast Line]], with the line being adapted in order to allow a shared service between Metro and rail services \u2013 therefore becoming the first system in the [[United Kingdom]] to implement a form of the [[Karlsruhe model]].<ref name=\"railwaytechnology\" /> Between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]], intermediate stations at [[Brockley Whins Metro station|Brockley Whins]], [[East Boldon Metro station|East Boldon]] and [[Seaburn Metro station|Seaburn]] were re-built, with a further three being purpose-built for the network, at [[Fellgate Metro station|Fellgate]], [[Stadium of Light Metro station|Stadium of Light]] and [[St Peter's Metro station|St. Peter's]]. Between [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]] and {{metro|South Hylton}}, around {{convert|3|mi|km|abbr=}} of the former [[Durham\u2013Sunderland line|Durham and Sunderland Railway]], which closed to passenger traffic in May 1964, was used as the alignment of the route. Five purpose-built stations at [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane]], [[University Metro station|University]], [[Millfield Metro station|Millfield]], [[Pallion Metro station|Pallion]] and [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]] were constructed for the network.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/p/penshaw_first/|title=Penshaw Station (1st site)|last=|first=|date=|website=Disused Stations|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Upgrades and development ==\n\n=== Project Orpheus ===\nIn 2002, Nexus unveiled an ambitious 15 year plan for transport in Tyne and Wear, named ''Project Orpheus''. The project, valued at \u00a31.5 billion, aimed to extend the existing Metro network, including links to [[Cramlington]], [[Doxford Park]], [[Killingworth]], [[MetroCentre (shopping centre)|Metrocentre]], [[Seaham]], [[Team Valley]] and [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]]. In addition to this, plans would see the introduction of street-running [[Tram|trams]], [[Water taxi|river buses]] across the [[River Tyne|Tyne]], and [[Aerial lift|cable cars]], linking 29 key corridors.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/1993003.stm|title=Tram rides for Tyneside|date=2002-05-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-18|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2568997.stm|title=Trams closer for Tyne and Wear|date=2002-12-12|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-18|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/road-tram-plan-stuck-amber-1628673|title=Road tram plan stuck on amber|last=|first=|date=2004-08-26|website=ChronicleLive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> The project has since been abandoned, with plans reworked and developed into the ''Metro: All Change'' programme.\n\n=== Metro: All Change ===\n\n==== Phase 1 ====\nThe first phase of Metro's ''All Change'' programme saw the start of a \u00a325 million project to install new ticket machines at all 60 stations across the network. Unlike the former ticket machines, which only accepted payment with coins, the new machines are able to accept payment with credit and debit card (with an upgrade to accept [[contactless payment]] in 2013),<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metro-passengers-feel-benefit-contactless-payment|title=Metro passengers feel the benefit of contactless payment|last=|first=|date=13 January 2014|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> notes and coins.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-16126081|title=Revamp for Metro ticket machines|date=2011-12-11|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-17|language=en-GB}}</ref> Automated ticket barriers (at 13 stations), and smart card validators at all stations across the network were also introduced, as part of the first phase of the ''All Change'' programme.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/city-metro-stations-get-new-smart-ticket-machines-and-gates|title=City Metro stations get new smart ticket machines and gates|last=|first=|date=22 October 2012|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/pop-card-validators-metro-stations-are-put-through-their-paces|title=Pop card validators at Metro stations are put through their paces|last=|first=|date=21 March 2013|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first phase of the programme also saw the completion of a new station at [[Simonside Metro station|Simonside]], in March 2008,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Rail-News/Nexus-announces-new-Metro-station|title=Nexus announces new Metro station|last=|first=|date=7 March 2008|website=Rail Technology Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> as well as the refurbishment and modernisation of [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-invest-%C2%A340m-metro-modernisation-over-next-12-months|title=Nexus to invest \u00a340m in Metro modernisation over the next 12 months|last=|first=|date=17 June 2015|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> An upgrade of platforms at [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]], and the refurbishment and modernisation of several other stations was also undertaken during this phase. Lifts and escalators have also been replaced at several stations, between 2009 and 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-completes-%C2%A31m-metro-lift-replacement-project|title=Nexus completes \u00a31m Metro lift replacement project|last=|first=|date=10 December 2009|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metro-says-goodbye-its-last-original-escalator|title=Metro says goodbye to its last original escalator|last=|first=|date=23 March 2016|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/new-escalators-city-centre-metro-stations|title=New escalators for city centre Metro stations|last=|first=|date=26 April 2012|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Phase 1 of the programme also involved the overhaul of infrastructure, including communications, track and overhead power lines, structures and embankments.\n\n==== Phase 2 ====\nPhase 2 of the ''All Change'' programme saw the \u00a320 million refurbishment of 86 [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]] (originally all 90 [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]] were due to be refurbished). Each [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocar]] was stripped down to its frame and built back up again, with the addition of improved disabled access, new door control systems, and renewed interiors, seating and lighting. A new cadmium yellow and black livery was also adopted. Work commenced in June 2010, at [[Wabtec Corporation|Wabtec]] in [[Doncaster]], and was completed five months ahead of schedule, in August 2015.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metrocar-takes-road-%C2%A320m-refurbishment-begins|title=Metrocar takes to road as \u00a320m refurbishment begins|last=|first=|date=22 June 2010|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/tyne-and-wear-metro-fleet-refurbishment-complete/41205.article|title=Tyne & Wear Metro fleet refurbishment complete|last=|first=|date=3 August 2015|website=Railway Gazette International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"RTM2014\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/wabtec-awarded-tyne-and-wear-metro-refurbishment-contract/35059.article|title=Wabtec awarded Tyne & Wear Metro refurbishment contract|last=|first=|date=11 June 2010|website=Railway Gazette International|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> The first [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocar]] to receive refurbishment was 4041, the unit being named after former Gateshead Councillor and MP, [[Harry Cowans]], in honour of his work in the 1970s, to help to secure the construction of the network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/first-refurbished-metro-train-re-dedicated|title=First refurbished Metro train re-dedicated|last=|first=|date=31 October 2011|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe second phase of the programme also saw the modernisation of a further 45 stations, including the re-building of the station at [[North Shields metro station|North Shields]], which was completed in September 2012,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metro-line-re-opens-wallsend-tynemouth|title=Metro line re-opens Wallsend-Tynemouth|last=|first=|date=2 September 2012|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> as well as the installation of new communications system, and the overhaul and maintenance of structures such as bridges, tunnels, track and overhead power lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-starts-biggest-engineering-project-metro-system-was-built|title=Nexus starts biggest engineering project on Metro since the system was built|last=|first=|date=10 March 2011|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Phase 3 ====\nThe third phase of Metro's ''All Change'' programme began in 2019, with the procurement of a new fleet of 46 (originally 42) units, designed by [[Switzerland|Swiss]] manufacturer, [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]]. Delivery of the new rolling stock will commence towards the end of 2021, with all units introduced in to passenger service by 2024 \u2013 replacing the current fleet of [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/modes/stadler-to-build-tyne-and-wear-metro-fleet/55643.article|title=Stadler to build Tyne & Wear metro fleet|last=|first=|date=28 January 2020|website=Railway Gazette International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-and-stadler-officially-sign-contract-new-metro-train-fleet|title=Nexus and Stadler officially sign the contract for a new Metro train fleet|last=|first=|date=11 February 2020|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> It will also see the introduction of a new signalling system, overhaul and maintenance of structures, track and overhead lines, and further station improvements.\n\n=== Maintenance and Renewals Skills Centre ===\nIn July 2018, Nexus announced the beginning of work to construct the new Maintenance and Renewals Skills Centre, at Mile End Road in [[South Shields]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/work-starts-ps84m-nexus-learning-centre-south-shields|title=Work starts on \u00a38.4m Nexus Learning Centre in South Shields|last=|first=|date=24 July 2018|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-ps84m-rail-training-centre-south-shields-gets-green-light|title=Nexus' \u00a38.4m rail training centre in South Shields gets the green light|last=|first=|date=22 March 2018|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-build-ps84m-rail-training-centre-south-shields|title=Nexus to build \u00a38.4m rail training centre in South Shields|last=|first=|date=28 November 2017|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> The \u00a38.4 million project will see the construction of a three-storey training centre, with classrooms, a mock control room, driver training simulator, covered tracks and inspection pits, and a mock Metro station, as well as a {{convert|70|m|ft|abbr=on}} stretch of dual track, to be used to carry out infrastructure training, including track, points, signalling and overhead line. The site will also be used to stable and maintain a small number of vehicles.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gallifordtry.co.uk/news/news-centre/galliford-try-appointed-to-tyneside-rail-project/|title=Galliford Try appointed to Tyneside rail project|last=|first=|date=28 November 2017|website=Galliford Try|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Metro Flow ===\nIn March 2020, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] announced a \u00a3103 million scheme, known as ''Metro Flow'', during the 2020 [[Budget of the United Kingdom|Budget]]. The project aims to increase frequency from 5 to 6 trains per hour, reduce journey times and improve service reliability. From September 2022, the project will see three sections of single line between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Bede Metro station|Bede]] converted to dual use, with an existing freight-only line electrified, and re-designed to operate using a similar system to the shared line between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]]. As part of the project, four additional [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] units have been funded, bringing the total number of units on order from 42 to 46.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/our-ps100m-project-boost-frequency-and-reliability-metro|title=Our \u00a3100m project to boost frequency and reliability on Metro|last=|first=|date=11 March 2020|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/uk/rail-in-the-2020-budget/55997.article|title=Rail in the 2020 budget|last=|first=|date=11 March 2020|website=Railway Gazette International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Service and frequency==\n\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro network consists of two lines:\n\n*'''Green Line:''' [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]] to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]]\n*'''Yellow Line:''' [[South Shields Metro station|South Shields]] to [[St. James Metro station|St. James]] via [[Whitley Bay Metro station|Whitley Bay]]\n\nServices commence between 05:00 and 06:00 (between 06:00 and 07:00 on Sunday), with frequent trains running until around midnight. Each line runs up to every 12 minutes during the day (Monday to Saturday), and up to every 15 minutes during the evening and on Sunday. This allows for a combined frequency of up to every 6 minutes (Monday to Saturday), and up to every 7\u20138 minutes during the evening and on Sunday, between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]]  and [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]]. Additional trains run during morning and evening peak hours (Monday to Friday) between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Regent Centre Interchange|Regent Centre]] or [[Monkseaton Metro station|Monkseaton]]. This provides a Metro up to every 3 minutes between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]], at peak times. Originally, there was also a Red Line between Heworth (later Pelaw) and Benton and a Blue Line between St James and North Shields. Additional trains ran on these lines during peak hours to increase the frequency at the busier stations.<ref name=\"SRT23\"/>\n{|\n|-\n|{{TWM Green line RDT}}{{nb5}}{{TWM Yellow line RDT}}\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n== Fleet and operations ==\n===Control Centre===\nThe Metro Control Centre is based at [[Gosforth]], in a building alongside the station at [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]]. It is responsible for operating the network's signalling and electrical supply, as well as being used to communicate with train drivers and other staff, using two-way radio equipment.<ref name=\":9\" /> The original equipment at the control centre was replaced in 2007,<ref name=\"railwaytechnology\" /> with a new computerised signalling control system installed in August 2018, at a cost of \u00a312 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.railway-technology.com/news/nexus-modernise-tyne-wear-metro-control-room-uk/|title=Nexus to modernise Tyne and Wear Metro control room in UK|date=2018-07-16|website=Railway Technology|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nexus.org.uk/news/item/watch-timelapse-video-ps12m-metro-control-room-revamp|title=Watch: timelapse video of \u00a312m Metro control room revamp|last=|first=|date=21 August 2018|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Depots===\n{{main|South Gosforth TMD}}\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro is currently operated from a single depot, also based in [[Gosforth]]. The depot opened in 1923, by the [[London and North Eastern Railway]], and was used to house the former [[Tyneside Electrics|''Tyneside Electrics'']] stock. The depot was inherited by Metro, prior to the system's opening in August 1980.<ref name=\"gosdep\">{{cite web|url=http://thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/stations/Gosforth_depot|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Stations: Gosforth depot|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> The depot is located at the centre of the triangular fork between the branch to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]], and the northern leg of the [[North Tyneside Loop]]. It is situated between stations at [[Longbenton Metro station|Longbenton]], [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]] and [[Regent Centre Interchange|Regent Centre]], and is used for stabling, cleaning, maintenance and repair of the fleet. It can be accessed by trains from either east or west, and there is also a depot-avoiding line running from east to west, which is not used in public service. \n\nPrior to the arrival of new rolling stock towards the end of 2021, a new depot is currently being constructed near [[Howdon]], in [[North Tyneside]]. The site will be used as a temporary stabling and maintenance facility for up to 10 [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]], whilst the current depot at [[South Gosforth TMD|South Gosforth]] is reconfigured. The temporary depot at [[Howdon]] is expected to open during summer 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/work-starts-temporary-metro-depot-north-tyneside|title=Work starts on a temporary Metro depot in North Tyneside|last=|first=|date=11 July 2019|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/temporary-metro-depot-takes-shape-north-tyneside|title=Temporary Metro depot takes shape in North Tyneside|last=|first=|date=2 January 2020|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> A further vehicle stabling and maintenance facility is also scheduled to open in [[South Tyneside]], as part of the Maintenance and Renewals Skills Centre at [[South Shields]].<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n=== Current fleet ===\n{{main|Tyne & Wear Metrocars}}\nSince the Tyne and Wear Metro opened in 1980, it has operated using the same rolling stock. The fleet comprises a total of 89 (originally 90) articulated units, known as [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|''Metrocars'']], which are numbered 4001\u20134090. When in service, Metrocars are normally coupled together in pairs, and have a maximum speed of {{convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. The first units to be built were two prototypes, numbered 4001 and 4002, which were delivered for testing in 1975. These were followed by 88 production units, which were built between 1978 and 1981. The design of the Metrocar was based on the [[Stadtbahnwagen B]], a [[Germany|German]] [[light rail]] vehicle developed in the early 1970s. The units were built by [[Metro-Cammell]], [[Washwood Heath]].<ref name=\"TTMtrains\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/trains/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Trains|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/tyne-wear-metro-celebrates-40th-9363207|title=Tyne and Wear Metro celebrates its 40th birthday with a special journey|last=Southern|first=Keiran|date=31 May 2015|website=ChronicleLive|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SRT\" />\n\nThe fleet has been refurbished several times, and several liveries have been used. The original livery used at opening was cadmium yellow and white, in accordance with the colours used by the [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive]] at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tynesideheritagevehicles.co.uk/our_vehicles/group_vehicles/uvk290t.html|title=290 / UVK 290T|last=|first=|date=|website=Tyneside Heritage Vehicles|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref> A mid-life refurbishment of the fleet, carried out in-house, took place between 1995 and 2000, and a new livery was adopted consisting of red, green or blue bodies, with yellow front and rear ends, and triangles containing the ''Metro'' logo on the doors.<ref name=\"TTMtrains\" /><ref name=\"RTM2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Interviews/bringing-contracts-back-in-house|title=Bringing contracts back in-house|last=|first=|date=14 March 2014|website=Rail Technology Magazine|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"railwaytechnology\" />\n\nA \u00a320 million refurbishment of 86 Metrocars (originally all 90 were due to be refurbished) began in June 2010, with the goal of the refurbishment programme being to extend the service life of until 2025, prior to the delivery of new rolling stock. Each Metrocar was stripped down to its frame and built back up again, with the addition of improved disabled access, new door control systems, and renewed interiors, seating and lighting. A new black, grey and yellow livery was also adopted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/new-metro-train-colours-revealed|title=New Metro train colours revealed|last=|first=|date=7 October 2011|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Refurbishment work was completed five months ahead of schedule, in August 2015.<ref name=\"RTM2014\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Branding and livery\n|width=215 |height=165\n|align=center\n|footer=\n|File:Tynemouth station, with Metro train, 1980, geograph-5317028-by-Walter-Dendy,-deceased.jpg\n |alt1=1980-1990s\n |1980\u20131990s|File:Tyne and Wear Metro No 4064, Tanners Bank, Tynemouth, 24 May 2012.jpg\n |alt2=1990s-2010s\n |1990s\u20132010s|File:Metro train at South Shields (16873964346).jpg\n |alt3=2010s-present \n |2010s\u2013present}}\n\n===Future fleet===\nIn 2016, Nexus unveiled plans to secure funding of \u00a3550 million for a replacement fleet, with a target for them to be in service by the early 2020s.<ref name=\"CLMETRO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/1bn-plan-improve-metro-approved-11637441|title=\u00a31bn plan to improve the Metro approved by North East transport chiefs|last=O'Donoghue|first=Dan|date=20 July 2016|website=ChronicleLive|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Philip Hammond]] announced that the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] would contribute \u00a3337 million towards the new fleet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://netimesmagazine.co.uk/editorial/budget-provides-transport-boost-tyne-wear/|title=Budget provides transport boost for Tyne & Wear|last=|first=|date=30 November 2017|website=North East Times|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref> The proposed new fleet was planned to have dual voltage capability, able to operate on the Metro's existing 1.5 kV [[Direct current|DC]] electrification system, as well as the 25 kV [[Alternating current|AC]] used on the [[Network Rail]] network, to allow for expansion of Metro service. [[Battery (electricity)|Battery]] technology was considered.<ref name=\"Sundechoextend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/metro-bosses-unveil-plans-to-extend-network-including-direct-link-between-sunderland-and-south-tyneside-1-8016661|title=Metro bosses unveil plans to extend network, including direct link between Sunderland and South Tyneside|last=|first=|date=15 July 2016|website=Sunderland Echo|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GRN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalrailnews.com/2016/07/20/new-trains-and-expanded-network-put-forward-in-tyne-and-wear-metro-strategy/|title=New trains and expanded network put forward in Tyne and Wear Metro strategy|last=|first=|date=20 July 2016|website=Rail Engineer|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Rmagnewfleet\">{{cite book|last1=Pickering|first1=Graeme|title=Metro's new fleet receives the green light|publisher=[[Rail (magazine)|Rail Magazine]]|year=2017|isbn=|edition=6\u201319 December|location=|pages=62\u201367}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]], [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]], a [[Downer Rail]]/[[CRRC]] joint venture, [[Hitachi]] and [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] were short-listed to build the new fleet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/screenshot/https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/five-bidders-invited-negotiate-build-new-metro-fleet|title=Five bidders invited to negotiate to build a new Metro fleet|last=|first=|date=17 September 2018|website=Nexus|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131201847/https://web.archive.org/screenshot/https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/five-bidders-invited-negotiate-build-new-metro-fleet|archive-date=31 January 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Five shortlisted for new Tyne & Wear Metro fleet \u2013 contract worth \u00a3362m|date=2018|work=The Railway Magazine|access-date=|url-status=live|issue=1411|page=10}}</ref> [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] was awarded a contract to build and maintain 42 five carriage [[light rail]] vehicles in January 2020, with deliveries to commence in late 2021, and all trains to be in passenger service by 2024. The new trains will feature next stop audio-visual information displays, [[London Underground|Tube]]-style linear seating to increase capacity, wider doors and aisles, air conditioning, WiFi and charging points.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-51277602 Tyne and Wear Metro: Swiss firm Stadler to build new fleet] ''BBC News'' 28 January 2020</ref> Following the announcement of the \u00a3103 million ''Metro Flow'' project, in March 2020, four additional [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] units have been funded, bringing the total number of units on order from 42 to 46.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|width=800 |height=80\n|align=center\n|Tyne & Wear Metro New Stock w-pantograph.png|alt1=New rolling stock\n |Concept art of The new Tyne and Wear Metro rolling stock, built by [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]].}}\n\n===Ancillary vehicles===\nIn addition to passenger trains, the Tyne and Wear Metro also operate three battery-electric locomotives (numbered BL1\u2013BL3), which were manufactured by [[Hunslet Engine Company|Hunslet]] in 1988. As well as this, the company also operate a [[Plasser & Theurer|Plasser and Theurer]] ballast tamper, and 15 wagons, which are used for maintenance and repair work.\n\n== Ownership ==\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro is publicly owned, receiving funding from council tax payers and government. [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|Nexus]], which owns and manages the Metro, contracted out operations and train maintenance as part of a deal with the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]], in order to secure modernisation investment and operating subsidy for the system between 2010 and 2021. Nexus continued to set fares, frequency of services and operating hours. Opponents would suggest that this was privatisation by the back door, though some services had already been contracted out, such as cleaning of stations and ticket inspections. \n\nIn November 2008, Nexus invited potential bidders to declare an interest in a contract to run the operations side of the business on its behalf. The successful bidder was to obtain a seven-year contract commencing on 1 April 2010, with up to an additional two years depending on performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/news/2010/nexus-names-final-two-bidders-metro-operations-contract|title=Nexus names final two bidders for Metro operations contract|date=2 October 2009|publisher=Nexus|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> In February 2009, four bids were shortlisted: [[DB Regio]], [[MTR Corporation]], [[Serco-Abellio]], and an in-house bid from Nexus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/7864519.stm|title=Foreign bids for Metro contract|date=2 February 2009|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=3 February 2009}}</ref> By October 2009, the shortlist had been reduced to bids from DB Regio and Nexus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/8288315.stm|title=Final shortlist for Metro service|date=3 October 2009|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=3 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, DB Regio was named as the preferred bidder, with the contract for operating the system signed in February 2010, and the handover of the service taking place in April 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|date=3 December 2009|title=DB Regio preferred bidder for Tyne & Wear Metro operating contract|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/10/db-regio-preferred-bidder-for-tyne-metro-operating-contract.html|journal=[[Railway Gazette International]]}}</ref><ref name=\"nexusfeb3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/news/2010/%C2%A3580-million-funding-gives-metro-world-class-future|title=\u00a3580 Million Funding Gives Metro a World-Class Future|last=|first=|date=3 February 2010|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> One of DB Regio's first initiatives was the ''Metro Dig It'' programme, and involved the re-painting of stations and deep-cleaning of stations and trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro-dig-it.co.uk|title=Metro - Dig It!|last=|first=|date=|website=Metro - Dig It!|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403131658/http://www.metro-dig-it.co.uk/|archivedate=3 April 2010|accessdate=31 March 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In February 2010, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] confirmed it would award Nexus up to \u00a3580 million to modernise and operate the Tyne and Wear Metro, with up to \u00a3350 million to be spent on the ''Metro: All Change'' programme, over the course of the following eleven years. A further \u00a3230 million would support running and maintenance costs, over the following nine years.<ref name=\"nexusfeb3\" />\n\nIn March 2016, Nexus announced that they did not intend to renew the contract with DB Regio, following the contract ending in 2017, after stating that they were dissatisfied with the operator due to missed performance targets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/frustrated-metro-delays-youre-right-12105683|title=Frustrated by Metro delays? You're right to be \u2013 report reveals string of missed targets|last=|first=|date=|website=ChronicleLive|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref> In April 2017, Nexus took over direct operation of the system for a planned period of two years, with the intention to re-tender the contract. The [[National Union of Rail, Maritime and Transport Workers|RMT]] trade union, however, has argued that the direct operation should be made permanent, and operation of the system should remain in public ownership.<ref name=\"Conend\" /><ref name=\"Metpublic\" /> As of March 2020, the Tyne and Wear Metro network is still under public ownership, with services operated by Nexus.\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n===Stations===\n{{See also|List of Tyne and Wear Metro stations}}\n\nThe 60 stations on the Tyne and Wear Metro network vary widely in character. Some are former [[British Rail]] stations, whilst others were purpose-built for the Metro. Most of the stations are above ground, but several in central [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[Gateshead]] are underground, namely [[Central Station Metro station|Central]], {{metro|Jesmond}}, {{metro|Haymarket}}, {{metro|Monument}}, {{metro|Manors}}, [[St James Metro station|St. James]] and [[Gateshead Interchange|Gateshead]]. In [[Sunderland]], [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane]] and {{stn|Sunderland}} stations also have underground platforms.<ref name=\"TTstations2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/stations/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Stations|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref> Four of the stations on the network, Central, Heworth, Manors and Sunderland, allow for interchange with [[National Rail]] services. {{stn|Sunderland}} is unique, in that it is the only station in the [[United Kingdom where [[Light rail|light]] and [[heavy rail]] services use the same platforms.\n\nGenerally, all Metro stations are unstaffed, with the exception of the underground stations, and gated stations when the ticket barriers are closed. All stations are equipped with ticket machines, shelters and seating, next train information displays, and emergency help points.<ref name=\"TTstations\" /> Ticket machines are able to accept payment with credit and debit card (including [[contactless payment]]), notes and coins.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":12\" /> Automated ticket barriers (at 13 stations), and smart card validators at all stations, were also installed during the first phase of Metro's ''All Change'' programme.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> Despite the majority of stations being open to access, the Tyne and Wear Metro has the third-highest level of passenger income per year (\u00a345.2 million in 2013/2014) of the eight [[light rail]] networks in [[England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/320645/light-rail-and-tram-statistics-2013-14.pdf|title=Light Rail and Tram Statistics: England 2013/14|last=|first=|date=17 June 2014|website=Department for Transport|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Regular checks are made by patrols of inspectors, both at stations and on board trains. Passengers caught travelling on the Metro without a ticket are subject to a \u00a320 [[penalty fare]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro/tickets/penalty-fares|title=Penalty Fares|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Stations\n|width=215 |height=165\n|align=center\n|1=File:Haymarket Metro station, 20 September 2010 (4).jpg|2=[[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], the first underground Metro station to be refurbished, branded in the new corporate colour scheme.|5=St Peter's Metro station, 8 September 2006.jpg|6=[[St Peter's Metro station|St. Peter's]], a purpose-built station, constructed in the early 2000s, following the Metro's extension to [[Wearside]].|7=Wansbeck Road Metro station, Tyne & Wear (geograph 4254512).jpg|8=[[Wansbeck Road Metro station|Wansbeck Road]], a purpose-built station, which opened in May 1981, following the Metro's extension to [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]].|9=Metro Station, Whitley Bay - geograph.org.uk - 1707495.jpg|10=[[Whitley Bay Metro station|Whitley Bay]], one of the network's former [[British Rail]] stations, located on the [[North Tyneside Loop]].}}\n\n=== Bicycles ===\nMost stations on the network have cycle racks, with smart cycle lockers located at 21 stations across the network (as of March 2020).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/cycle/cycle-lockers|title=Cycle lockers|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Following a trial period in 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metro-holds-limited-trial-allowing-people-travel-non-folding-bikes|title=Metro holds limited trial allowing people to travel with non-folding bikes|last=|first=|date=30 March 2016|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> non-folding bicycles are permitted to travel on Metro between 10:00 and 15:00 and after 19:00 on weekdays, and all day at weekends, between [[Callerton Parkway Metro station|Callerton Parkway]] or [[Manors Metro station|Manors]] and [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], and between [[Gateshead Stadium Metro station|Gateshead Stadium]] and [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]] or [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]]. Non-folding bicycles are not permitted to travel between [[Callerton Parkway Metro station|Callerton Parkway]] and [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]], or between [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]] and [[Gateshead Stadium Metro station|Gateshead Stadium]] at any time. Folding bicycles are permitted to travel without restriction, across the entire Metro network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nexus.org.uk/cycle/bikes-metro-trial|title=Bikes on Metro trial|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro/looking-after-our-passengers/bikes-metro|title=Bikes on Metro|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Tunnels ===\n[[File:TWM tunnels.png|thumb|A map of the network in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[Gateshead]]. Metro routes are shown in red, with dotted red lines displaying tunnel sections.]]\nUnder [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], two routes run underground at right angles to each other, and intersect at [[Monument Metro station|Monument]], which has four platforms on two levels. The first route, shared by both the Green Line (from [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]] to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]]) and Yellow Line (from [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]] to [[St James Metro station|St. James]]), runs from north to south. It heads underground at [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], and runs south through {{metro|Haymarket}}, [[Monument Metro station|Monument]] and [[Central Station Metro station|Central]], before rising above ground to cross the [[Queen Elizabeth II Bridge, Newcastle upon Tyne|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge]] over the [[River Tyne]]. It then enters another tunnel, running underneath [[Gateshead]], serving [[Gateshead Interchange|Gateshead]], before rising above ground again before the station at [[Gateshead Stadium Metro station|Gateshead Stadium]].<ref name=\"TTPELGOS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/pelaw-gosforth/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Routes : Pelaw \u2013 Gosforth|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe second underground route, part of the Yellow Line (from [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]] to [[St James Metro station|St. James]]), runs from east to west, heading underground after running east alongside the [[East Coast Main Line]], before serving [[Manors Metro station|Manors]] and [[Monument Metro station|Monument]], then terminating at [[St James Metro station|St. James]].<ref name=\"TTNTL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/tynecoastloop/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro : Routes : North Tyneside Loop|publisher=TheTrams|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref> Yellow Line trains pass through [[Monument Metro station|Monument]] twice, once eastbound through the east-west platforms, and then, after running around the [[North Tyneside Loop]], southbound through the north-south platforms before running to [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]].<ref name=\"TAGBI\"/>\n\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro is one of the few rapid transit systems in the world with a [[pretzel|''pretzel'']] configuration, in which a line crosses over itself and trains pass through the same station twice at different platforms. This arrangement also exists at [[Voorweg RandstadRail station|Voorweg]] on the [[Randstadrail|RandstadRail]] network in [[The Hague]], and at [[Serdika Metro Station|Serdika]], on the [[Sofia Metro]] in [[Bulgaria]].\n\nA short spur line, running partly under a tunnel, runs from [[Manors Metro station|Manors]] to [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]]. The line is used for empty stock movements only, and has no passenger service. Before the Metro tunnels were created, it was part of the main rail route to [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]], and connected to the main line at [[Manors railway station|Manors]].<ref name=\"TTPELGOS\" />\n\nThe tunnels were constructed in the late 1970s, using mining techniques, and were constructed as single-track tubes with a diameter of {{convert|4.75|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /> The tunnels under [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] were mechanically bored through [[boulder clay]], and lined with cast iron or concrete segments. The tunnel under [[Gateshead]] was bored through [[sandstone]] and excavated coal seams. Old coal mine workings, some of which dated from the [[Middle Ages]], had to be filled in before the tunnelling began.<ref name=\":9\" /> \n\n===Distances===\nDistances on the system are measured from a datum point at [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/tw_metro_station_distances|title=TW Metro Station Distances - a Freedom of Information request to Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|date=2013-01-18|website=WhatDoTheyKnow|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> The system is metric, with distances in kilometres, and rounded to the nearest metre. Lines are designated ''In'' and ''Out''. The ''In'' line runs from [[St James Metro station|St. James]] to [[South Shields Metro station|South Shields]] via the ''inside'' of the [[North Tyneside Loop]] (via [[Wallsend Metro station|Wallsend]] then [[Whitley Bay Metro station|Whitley Bay]]), with the ''Out'' line running in the opposite direction. By extension, the ''In'' line runs from [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]] to [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]], and from [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] to [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]].\n\nDistance plates are mounted on all [[Overhead lines#Overhead catenary|overhead line]] structures. Different distances are normally quoted for stations, depending on whether the direction of travel is ''In'' or ''Out''. Distances increase from the datum in all directions.<ref name=\"Maxey\">{{cite book|last=Maxey|first=David|title=Mile by Mile: Rail Mileages of Britain and Ireland|publisher=Peter Watts Publishing Limited|year=1987|isbn=9780906025444|location=Woodchester|pages=}}</ref> The part of line between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]] owned by [[Network Rail]] is dual-marked in both metric units, as well as miles and chains. The boundary between the two systems is located at Pelaw Junction.<ref name=\"Quail2\">{{cite book|last=Jacobs|first=Gerald|title=Railway Track Diagrams Book 2: Eastern|publisher=Trackmaps|year=2006|isbn=9780954986629|location=|pages=|coauthors=}}</ref> The closest adjacent stations by distance on the network are [[St Peter's Metro station|St. Peter's]] and [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]], with the furthest apart being [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Fellgate Metro station|Fellgate]].\n\n===Electrification===\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro is electrified with [[overhead lines]] at [[railway electrification in Great Britain#1,500 V DC, overhead|1,500 V DC]], and is now the only rail network in the [[United Kingdom]] to use this system.<ref name=railwaytechnology /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azocleantech.com/article.aspx?ArticleID=262|title=Are Electric Trains Eco-Friendly?|publisher=AZO Clean Tech|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref> Nexus have stated that their long term ambition is to convert the electrification of the line between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]], which is shared with [[heavy rail]], to the [[Network Rail]] standard of [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25\u00a0kV AC]]. However, in doing this, a new fleet of dual voltage trains would be required.<ref name=\"Sundechoextend\"/><ref name=\"GRN\"/>\n\n==Ridership==\nDuring the 1985/86 financial year, the Tyne and Wear Metro carried a total of 59.1 million passengers \u2013 the highest figure it has ever achieved. By 1987/88, this had declined to 44.9 million. The decline was attributed to the loss of integration with bus services, following [[Bus deregulation in Great Britain|deregulation]] in 1986, as well as the general decline in public transport use in the area.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\"dftjour\">{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/719478/lrt0101.ods|title=Table LRT0101: Passenger journeys on light rail and trams by system: England - annual from 1983/84|last=|first=|date=14 June 2019|website=Department for Transport|publisher=|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> Usage continued to decline during the 1990s, reaching its lowest level during 2000/01. Since the turn of the century, passenger usage has risen and stabilised, fluctuating in a range of 35\u201340 million passengers annually. Prior to 2016/17, the Tyne and Wear Metro consistently ranked as the second-most used [[tram]] and [[light rail]] network in the [[United Kingdom]], after [[London]]'s [[Docklands Light Railway]]. The Metro is now ranked as the third-most used [[tram]] and [[light rail]] network in the [[United Kingdom]], after the [[Docklands Light Railway]], closely following the [[Manchester Metrolink]].<ref name=\"dftjour\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/809958/lrt9903.ods|title=Table LRT9903a: Edinburgh Trams statistics, annual from 2014/15|last=|first=|date=19 June 2019|website=Department for Transport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/852322/lrt9902.ods|title=Table LRT9902a: Glasgow Underground statistics, annual from 1982/83|last=|first=|date=|website=Department for Transport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n | width=500\n | height=250\n | xAxisTitle=Year\n | yAxisTitle=Passenger journeys (million)\n | legend=Operator\n | type=line\n | x= 1984, 1985, 1986, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1990, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n| y1 = 6.2, 6.0, 6.2, 6.2, 5.4, 5.4, 5.6, 5.8, 5.0, 5.2, 5.5, 5.4, 4.9, 4.9, 4.7, 4.4, 4.3, 4.1, 4.9, 4.5, 3.7, 3.9, 3.6, 3.4, 2.9, 2.3, 2.2, 1.6, 1.1, 3.7, 4.3, 4.1, 4.9, 5.1, 5.2, 5.2\n| y2 = {{repeat|31|, }} 4.1, 5.3, 5.8, 7.5, 7.5\n| y3 = 12.3, 12.7, 13.1, 13.7, 13.6, 13.6, 13.5, 13.7, 13.6, 13.5, 14.3, 14.7, 14.3, 13.7, 14.1, 14.6, 14.7, 14.4, 13.8, 13.4, 13.3, 13.3, 13.2, 13.5, 14.5, 14.1, 13.1, 13.0, 12.9, 12.6, 12.7, 13.0, 11.4, 11.1, 13.1, 13.1\n| y4 = {{repeat|9|, }} 8.1, 11.3, 12.3, 12.6, 13.4, 13.8, 13.2, 14.2, 17.2, 18.2, 18.8, 18.9, 19.7, 19.9, 19.8, 20.0, 21.1, 19.6, 19.2, 22.3, 25.0, 29.2, 31.2, 34.3, 37.8, 41.2, 43.7\n| y5 = {{repeat|16|, }} 4.8, 5.4, 4.8, 4.9, 5.1, 5.0, 5.1, 4.9, 4.8, 4.7, 4.7, 4.8, 4.9, 4.8, 4.7, 4.4, 4.8, 6.2, 5.7, 5.9\n| y6 = {{repeat|20|, }} 0.4, 8.5, 9.8, 10.1, 10.2, 9.8, 9.0, 9.7, 9.0, 7.4, 7.9, 8.1, 12.2, 16.4, 17.8, 18.8\n| y7 = {{repeat|11|, }} 2.2, 5.3, 7.8, 9.2, 10.4, 10.9, 11.1, 11.4, 11.5, 12.3, 12.8, 13.1, 14.0, 14.8, 15.0, 14.7, 15.0, 15.0, 14.4, 12.6, 11.5, 11.6, 12.6, 12.3, 11.9\n| y8 = 49.8, 57.2, 59.1, 46.4, 44.9, 45.4, 45.5, 43.6, 40.6, 38.9, 38.3, 37, 35.9, 35.4, 35, 33.8, 32.7, 32.5, 33.4, 36.6, 37.9, 36.8, 35.8, 37.9, 39.8, 40.6, 40.8, 39.9, 37.9, 37, 35.7, 38.1, 40.3, 37.7, 36.4, 36.4\n | y1Title=Blackpool Tramway\n | y2Title=Edinburgh Trams\n | y3Title=Glasgow Subway\n | y4Title=Manchester Metrolink\n | y5Title=West Midland Metro\n | y6Title=Nottingham Express Transit\n | y7Title=Sheffield Supertram\n | y8Title=Tyne and Wear Metro\n | colors=#5f195e, #b31b1b, #c26b00, #ffdb4e, #0075bf, #01796f, #000000, #feb300\n}}\n\n== Branding and identity ==\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro has a distinctive [[design]] and [[corporate identity]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/metro_design_guide|title=Metro Design Guide - a Freedom of Information request to Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|date=2018-04-18|website=WhatDoTheyKnow|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> initially developed to distinguish itself from the antiquated rail system it replaced in the 1980s, as well as to match the livery of the buses operated by the Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive, prior to [[Bus deregulation in Great Britain|deregulation]] in 1986. The ''Calvert'' [[typeface]] was designed specifically for Metro by [[Margaret Calvert]], and is used extensively throughout the system, including on the distinctive black ''M'' logo on a yellow background. The logo is used to denote the Metro, and is featured on cube signs at station entrances, as well as on board trains, and on station signage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/history/how-tyne-wear-metro-made-12031209|title=How the Tyne and Wear Metro was made \u2013 we go back 36 years to the very beginning|last=Meechan|first=Simon|date=16 October 2016|website=ChronicleLive|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the branding identity of the Metro became inconsistent and confused in the late 1990s and early 2000s, Nexus employed a local design agency, Gardiner Richardson, to help the organisation to revive the brand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.designweek.co.uk/issues/may-2009-online/gardiner-richardson-rebrands-tyne-and-wear-metro/|title=Gardiner Richardson rebrands Tyne and Wear Metro|last=|first=|date=2009-05-20|website=Design Week|language=en-UK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> In 2009, as part of the ''Metro: All Change'' programme, re-branding began to take place. Re-branding saw an emphasis placed on the ''Calvert'' typeface on lettering, signage and maps. It also saw the introduction of a simplified colour scheme of black, white, grey and yellow, to be used on refurbished stations, signage and trains. In 2009, [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]] was the first station to be refurbished, using the new corporate branding and colour scheme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thebeautyoftransport.com/2017/04/19/m-is-for-metro-calvert-typeface-and-the-nexus-tyne-and-wear-public-transport-visual-identity/|title=M is for... Metro (Calvert Typeface and the Nexus Tyne and Wear Public Transport Visual Identity)|last=|first=|date=19 April 2017|website=The Beauty of Transport|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-invest-%C2%A340m-metro-modernisation-over-next-12-months|title=Nexus to invest \u00a340m in Metro modernisation over the next 12 months|last=|first=|date=17 June 2015|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Branding and signage\n|width=215 |height=150\n|align=center\n|1=Newcastle Metro sign.jpg|2=The Metro cube sign \u2013 a common sight at stations across the Metro network.|3=Haymarket Metro station, 20 September 2010 (5).jpg|4=A platform at [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], branded in the new corporate colour scheme.|5=Haymarket Metro station, 20 September 2010 (6).jpg|6=Station signage at [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], branded in the new corporate colour scheme.|7=Jesmond Metro station, 10 April 2010 (1).jpg|8=A platform at [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], branded in the original corporate colour scheme.|9=Jesmond Metro station, 20 September 2010.jpg|10=Station signage at [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], branded in the original corporate colour scheme.}}\n\n== Art ==\n\nThere are more than 30 pieces of permanent art across the transport network in Tyne and Wear. A number of Metro stations feature commissioned works by various artists, including:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport|title=Art on transport|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*'''Haymarket:''' ''Canon'' (2010) by Lothar Goetz<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/canon-lothar-goetz|title='Canon' by Lothar Goetz|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*'''Jarrow:''' ''Jarrow March'' (1984) by Vince Rea<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/jarrow-march-vince-rea|title='Jarrow March' by Vince Rea|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*'''Monkseaton:''' ''Beach and Shipyards'' (1983) by Mike Davies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/beach-shipyards-mike-davies|title='Beach & Shipyards' by Mike Davies|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''Monument:''' ''Parson's Polygon'' (1985) by David Hamilton<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/parsons-polygon-david-hamilton|title='Parsons Polygon' by David Hamilton|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''Queen Elizabeth II Bridge:''' ''Nocturne'' (2007) by Nayan Kulkarni<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/nocturne-nayan-kulkarni|title='Nocturne' by Nayan Kulkarni|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*'''Sunderland:''' ''Platform 5'' (2011) by Jason Bruges Studio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/platform-5-jason-bruges-studio|title='Platform 5' by Jason Bruges Studio|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jasonbruges.com/platform-5|title=Platform 5|website=Jason Bruges Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*'''Wallsend:''' ''Pontis'' (2003) by Michael Pinsky<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/pontis-michael-pinsky|title='Pontis' by Michael Pinsky|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n{{Gallery\n|title=Art\n|width=215 |height=165\n|align=center\n|footer=\n|Haymarket Metro station, 20 September 2010 (8).jpg|alt1=\n |Canon (2010)|Parsons Polygon, Blackett Street (geograph 1697679).jpg|alt2=\n |Parson's Polygon (1985)|Hadrian's Wall - Tyne and Wear Metro style.jpg|alt3= \n |Pontis (2003)}}\n==Proposed future upgrades and development==\n===Extension to Washington IAMP===\nThere have been a number of proposals looking in to the possibility of re-opening the former [[Leamside line|Leamside Line]] to [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]], including a 2009 report from the [[Association of train operating companies|Association of Train Operating Companies (ATOC)]],{{ATOCConnectingCommunitiesReportS10}} and a 2016 proposal from the [[North East Combined Authority|North East Combined Authority (NECA)]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://northeastca.gov.uk/news/neca-sets-out-bold-ambitions-metro-and-local-rail-services/|title=NECA sets out bold ambitions for Metro and local rail services|date=2016-07-19|website=North East Combined Authority|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> as well as the abandoned ''Project Orpheus'' programme, from the early 2000s. Most recently, proposals are being put forward to link the current network at [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]], with the International Advanced Manufacturing Park in [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]], using part of the alignment of the former [[Leamside line|Leamside Line]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/hopes-metro-could-extended-business-15652152|title=Hopes Metro could be extended to business park near Sunderland's Nissan plant|last=Harrison|first=James|date=2019-01-10|website=ChronicleLive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shieldsgazette.com/news/politics/council/detailed-talks-underway-extend-metro-south-tyneside-and-sunderland-serve-iamp-2503956|title='Detailed talks' underway to extend Metro to serve giant new business park|last=Harrison|first=James|date=22 March 2020|website=The Shields Gazette|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Durham Coast Line]]\n* [[Leamside line|Leamside Line]]\n* [[List of Tyne and Wear Metro stations]]\n* [[North Tyneside Loop]]\n* [[South Gosforth TMD]]\n* [[Transport in Tyne and Wear]]\n* [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Tyne and Wear Metrocars]]\n* [[Tyneside Electrics]]\n* [[Urban rail in the United Kingdom]]\n\n== References ==\n{{clear}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite magazine|title=A line for all Geordies|first=Peter|last=Kelly|magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|Rail Enthusiast]]|publisher=EMAP National Publications|date=December 1981 \u2013 January 1982|pp=48\u201351|issn=0262-561X|oclc=49957965}}\n*{{cite magazine|title=Metro miracle is complete|first=Murray|last=Brown|magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|Rail Enthusiast]]|publisher=EMAP National Publications|date=June 1984|pp=23\u201325|issn=0262-561X|oclc=49957965}}\n*{{cite magazine|title=New liveries for Tyne & Wear Metro|first=Robin|last=Etherington|page=10|issue=93|date=6\u201319 April 1989|magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|RAIL]]|publisher=EMAP National Publications|issn=0953-4563|oclc=49953699}}\n*{{cite magazine|title=Geordie's canny Metro heads for Wearside|first=Phil|last=Haigh|magazine=[[RAIL (magazine)|RAIL]]|issue=319|publisher=EMAP Apex Publications|date=3\u201316 December 1997|pp=30\u201334|issn=0953-4563|oclc=49953699}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Tyne and Wear Metro}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n*[http://www.traintesting.com/Metro.htm Commissioning the Sunderland Direct extension in 2002]\n*[http://www.identifont.com/show?H3 Identifont \u2013 Calvert]\n*[http://www.nexus.org.uk/ Nexus website]\n*[https://www.nexus.org.uk/themes/custom/nexus/images/metro-map-large.jpg Tyne and Wear Metro network map]\n*{{Official website|http://www.nexus.org.uk/metro|Tyne and Wear Metro website}}\n\n{{Tyne and Wear Metro network}}\n{{UK light rail}}\n{{Britishmetros}}\n{{Underground rapid transit in the European Union}}\n{{Internationally Metro Organizations}}\n{{Airport rail links in the United Kingdom}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tyne and Wear Metro| ]]\n[[Category:1500 V DC railway electrification]]\n[[Category:Airport rail links in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Arriva Group companies]]\n[[Category:Electric railways in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Light rail in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1980]]\n[[Category:Railway loop lines]]\n[[Category:Transport in Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:Transport in the City of Sunderland|Metro]]\n[[Category:Transport in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive]]\n[[Category:Underground rapid transit in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Rapid-transit rail network in north-east England}}\n{{redirect|Newcastle Metro|the light rail system in Newcastle, Australia|Newcastle Light Rail}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox public transit\n| box_width = 340px\n| name = Tyne and Wear Metro\n| image = Tyne Wear Metro logo.svg\n| imagesize = 70px\n| image2 = 4057 at Monument Metro station, Newcastle, 20 June 2015 (crop).jpg\n| imagesize2 = 300px\n| caption2 = A [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocar]] at [[Monument Metro station|Monument]], branded in the current black and yellow corporate livery.\n| image3 = Tyne & Wear Metro diagram.png\n| imagesize3 = 300px\n| caption3 = A schematic map of the Tyne and Wear Metro network.\n| locale = [[Tyne and Wear]]\n| transit_type = {{plainlist|\n* [[Light rail]]\n* [[Rapid transit]]\n}}\n| lines = [[#Routes and services|2]]\n| stations = [[List of Tyne and Wear Metro stations|60]]\n| annual_ridership = 36.4 million (2018/19)<ref name=\"2018/19DfTstats\">{{cite web |title=Light Rail and Tram Statistics, England: 2018/19 |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/809894/light-rail-and-tram-statistics-england-2019.pdf |publisher=[[Department for Transport]] |access-date=19 June 2019}}</ref><br>{{increase}} 0.1%\n| headquarters = Station Road<br>[[Gosforth]]<br>[[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n| began_operation = 11 August 1980<br>({{Years or months ago|1980|8}})\n| owner = [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|Nexus]]\n| operator = Nexus\n| chief_executive = \n| vehicles = 89 [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]]\n| train_length = {{cvt|27.81|m|ftin}}\n| system_length = {{cvt|77.5|km|mi}}<ref name=\"TAGBI\"/>\n| track_gauge = {{RailGauge|sg|al=on}}\n| el = [[Overhead line]]<br>(1,500 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]])\n| minimum_radius_of_curvature = \n| top_speed = {{cvt|80|kph|mph}}\n| map_name = \n| map = \n| map_state = \n| website = https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| area served = {{plainlist|\n* [[Gateshead]]\n* [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n* [[North Tyneside]]\n* [[South Tyneside]]\n* [[Sunderland]]\n}}\n| line_number = \n| start = \n| end = \n| character = \n}}\n{{Tyne and Wear Metro}}\n\nThe '''Tyne and Wear Metro''' is a [[light rail]] network linking [[South Tyneside]] and [[Sunderland]] with [[Gateshead]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[North Tyneside]] and [[Newcastle International Airport|Newcastle Airport]]. The network opened in stages from August 1980, and now serves a total of 60 stations, with two lines covering {{convert|48.2|mi|km|abbr=}} of track.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://trl.co.uk/reports/CR357|title=The longer term effects of the Tyne and Wear Metro|last=Davoudi|first=S.|last2=Gillard|first2=A.|date=1 January 1993|website=TRL|publisher=|isbn=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=30 June 2018|last3=Healey|first3=P.|last4=Pullen|first4=B.|last5=Raybould|first5=S.|last6=Robinson|first6=F.|last7=Silcock|first7=D.|last8=Usher|first8=D.|last9=Wymer|first9=C.}}</ref><ref name=\"railwaytechnology\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/tyne/|title=Tyne & Wear Metro Rapid Transit System, United Kingdom|last=|first=|date=|website=Railway Technology|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=14 March 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TTstations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/stations/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Stations|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"TAGBI\" /> \n\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro has been described as the \"first modern light rail system in the [[United Kingdom]]\".<ref name=\"Metrobuilt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/history/how-metro-was-built|title=How Metro was built|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 April 2015}}</ref> In 2018\u201319, an estimated 36.4 million passenger journeys were made on the Metro, making it the third-most used [[tram]] and [[light rail]] network in the [[United Kingdom]], after [[London]]'s [[Docklands Light Railway]] (121.8 million passenger journeys) and the [[Manchester Metrolink]] (43.7 million passenger journeys).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/809894/light-rail-and-tram-statistics-england-2019.pdf|title=Light rail and tram statistics, England: 2018/19|last=|first=|date=19 June 2019|website=Department for Transport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe initial Tyne and Wear Metro network opened between August 1980 and March 1984, mostly using converted former railway lines, linked with new tunnel infrastructure. Further extensions to the original network were opened in November 1991 (from [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]] to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]]),<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metros-airport-extension-celebrates-its-25th-year|title=Metro's airport extension celebrates its 25th year|last=|first=|date=17 November 2016|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> and March 2002 (from [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] to [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]] and [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]]).<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/1905281.stm|title=Metro system extended to Sunderland|date=2002-04-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-18|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe system is [[#Ownership and operators|owned and operated]] by [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|Nexus]], having been formerly operated under contract by [[DB Regio]] from 2010 until April 2017, with Nexus taking over direct operation of the system, under public ownership.<ref name=\"Conend\">{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-35800733|title=Tyne and Wear Metro operator contract to end in 2017|date=14 March 2016|work=BBC News|accessdate=20 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Metpublic\">{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-39466348|title=Tyne and Wear Metro to be publicly run by Nexus|date=1 April 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=3 April 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Predecessor===\n{{main|Tyneside Electrics}}\nThe present system uses much former railway infrastructure, mostly constructed between 1834 and 1882, one of the oldest parts being the [[Newcastle & North Shields Railway|Newcastle and North Shields Railway]], which opened in 1839. In 1904, in response to [[Newcastle Corporation Tramways|tramway competition]] which was taking away passengers, the [[North Eastern Railway (United Kingdom)|North Eastern Railway]] started [[railway electrification in Great Britain|electrifying]] parts of their local railway network north of the [[River Tyne]] with a 600\u00a0[[Volt|V]] [[direct current|DC]] [[third-rail]] system, forming one of the earliest suburban electric networks, known as the [[Tyneside Electrics|''Tyneside Electrics'']]. In 1938, the line south of the [[River Tyne]] between [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and {{rws|South Shields}} was also electrified.\n\nUnder [[British Rail]] in the 1960s, the decision was made to de-electrify the ''Tyneside Electrics'' network and convert it to diesel operation, owing to falling passenger numbers and the cost of renewing end-of-life electrical infrastructure and rolling stock. The [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] to [[South Shields]] line was de-electrified in 1963, along with the [[North Tyneside]] routes, in 1967.<ref name=\"TAGBI\">{{cite book|last1=Schwandle|first1=Robert|title=Tram Atlas Britain & Ireland|date=|publisher=Robert Schwandl|year=2015|isbn=9783936573459|location=Berlin, Germany|pp=132\u2013137}}</ref><ref name=\"TNEE\">{{cite book|last1=Hoole|first1=K.|title=North Eastern Electrics: The History of the Tyneside Electric Passenger Services, 1904\u201367|date=|publisher=The Oakwood Press|year=1987|isbn=9780853613589|location=United Kingdom|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emus.co.uk/zone/tyneside/tyneside.htm|title=The Tyneside Electrics|last=|first=|date=|website=Suburban Electric Railway Association|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref> This was widely viewed as a backward step, as the [[diesel multiple unit|diesel trains]] were slower than the electric trains they replaced.<ref name=\"SRT23\">{{cite book|last1=Young|first1=Alan|title=Suburban Railways of Tyneside|date=|publisher=Martin Bairstow|year=1999|isbn=9781871944204|location=|page=23|pages=}}</ref>\n\n===Planning and construction===\nIn the early 1970s, the poor local transport system was identified as one of the main factors holding back the region's economy, and in 1971 a study was commissioned by the recently created [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Authority|Tyneside Passenger Transport Authority]] (now known as ''Nexus'') into how the transport system could be improved.\n\nThis study recommended reviving the badly run-down former Tyneside Electrics network by converting it into an electrified [[rapid transit]] system, which would include a new underground section to better serve the busy central areas of [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[Gateshead]], as it was felt that the existing rail network didn't serve these areas adequately. This new system was intended to be the core of a new integrated transport network, with buses acting as feeders to purpose-built transport interchanges. The plans were approved by the Tyneside Metropolitan Railway Bill, which was passed by [[Parliament]] in July 1973. Around 70% of the funding for the scheme came from a central [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] grant, with the remainder coming from local sources.<ref name=\"Nexus-history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/history/landmarks-urban-transport|title=Landmarks in urban transport|last=|first=|date=|year=|website=Nexus|publisher=Nexus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Meet Your Metro|publisher=Tyne and Wear Transport|year=June 1978|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n\nThree railway lines, totalling {{convert|26|mi|km|abbr=}} were to be converted into Metro lines as part of the initial system \u2013 these being the [[North Tyneside Loop]] and [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] to [[South Shields]] branch (both of which were formerly part of the ''Tyneside Electrics'' network), and a short stretch of the freight-only [[Ponteland Railway]] between {{Metro|South Gosforth}} and [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]], which had not seen any passenger traffic since 1929.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" />\n\nThe converted railway lines were to be connected by around {{convert|6|mi|km|abbr=}} of new infrastructure, which was built both to separate the Metro from the existing rail network, and also to create the new underground routes under [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[Gateshead]]. Around {{convert|4|mi|km|abbr=}} of the new infrastructure was in [[#Tunnels|tunnels]], whilst the remainder was either at ground level or elevated. The elevated sections included the [[Queen Elizabeth II Bridge, Newcastle upon Tyne|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge]], a new {{convert|350|m|ft|abbr=on|}} bridge carrying the Metro across the [[River Tyne]], and the {{convert|815|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[Byker Viaduct]] across the [[Ouseburn Valley]], between {{Metro|Byker}} and {{Metro|Manors}}.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> \n\nConstruction work began in October 1974. This involved the construction of the new infrastructure, re-electrifying the routes with [[overhead line]] equipment, the upgrading or relocation of existing stations, and the construction of several new stations, some of which were underground. By 1984, the final cost of the project was \u00a3265 million (equivalent to \u00a3{{Inflation|UK|265|1984|r=0|fmt=c}}&nbsp;million in {{CURRENTYEAR}}).<ref name=\"SRT\">{{cite book|last1=Young|first1=Alan|title=Suburban Railways of Tyneside|date=|publisher=Martin Bairstow|year=1999|isbn=9781871944204|location=|pages=90\u201394}}</ref>{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} The Tyne and Wear Metro was the first railway in the [[United Kingdom]] to operate using the [[metric system]], with all speeds and distances stated in [[metric units]] only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcts.org.uk/branches/north_east/page.htm?id=north%20east/metro|title=Guide to Travelling on the Tyne & Wear Metro|last=|first=|date=22 September 2011|website=Railway Correspondance and Travel Society (RCTS)|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> It was also the first transport system in the [[United Kingdom]] to be designed to be fully [[accessibility|accessible]] to passengers with disabilities, with step-free access available at all stations across the network.<ref name=\"CLmetrohistory\" />\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Construction of the Metro\n|width=215 |height=165\n|align=center\n|footer=\n|Haymarket Metro Station escalator shaft (8691421213).jpg|alt1=Tunnel\n |The escalator shaft at [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], under construction in the late 1970s.|Metro Bridge nearing completion, 1978 (25760168724).jpg|alt2=QEII Bridge\n |The [[Queen Elizabeth II Bridge, Newcastle upon Tyne|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge]] over the [[River Tyne]], nearing completion in 1978.|Tyne Dock Metro Station (8691436755).jpg|alt3=Tyne Dock \n |The Metro station at [[Tyne Dock Metro station|Tyne Dock]], under construction in the early 1980s.}}\n\n===Opening===\n\nOriginally, the Tyne and Wear Metro was intended to be opened in stages between 1979 and 1981.<ref name=\":9\" /> The first stages of the original network (between [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]] and [[Tynemouth Metro station|Tynemouth]]) opened in August 1980, with the final stage (between [[Heworth Interchange|Heworth]] and [[South Shields]]) opening in March 1984.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /> The opening dates of services and stations are as follows:<ref name=\"TAGBI\" />\n\n*'''11 August 1980:''' [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]] to [[Tynemouth Metro station|Tynemouth]] via [[Benton Metro station|Benton]]\n*'''10 May 1981:''' [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]] to [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]]\n*'''15 November 1981:''' [[Heworth Interchange|Heworth]] to [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]]\n*'''14 November 1982:''' [[St James Metro station|St. James]] to [[Tynemouth Metro station|Tynemouth]] via [[Wallsend Metro station|Wallsend]]\n*'''24 March 1984:''' [[Heworth Interchange|Heworth]] to [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]]\n*'''15 September 1985:''' [[Kingston Park Metro station|Kingston Park]]\n*'''16 September 1985:''' [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]]\n*'''19 March 1986:''' [[Palmersville Metro station|Palmersville]]\n*'''17 November 1991:''' [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]] to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]]\n*'''31 March 2002:''' [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] to [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]]\n*'''28 April 2002:''' [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane]]\n*'''11 December 2005:''' [[Northumberland Park Metro station|Northumberland Park]]\n*'''17 March 2008:''' [[Simonside Metro station|Simonside]]\n\n===Integration===\nWhen the Tyne and Wear Metro first opened, it was intended to form part of an [[integrated public transport]] system, with the local bus network reconfigured to act as 'feeder' services for the Metro. The Metro was intended to cover trunk journeys, while buses were re-designed towards shorter, local trips, to bring passengers to and from Metro stations, using [[unified ticketing]], and with their timetable integrated with the Metro schedule. Several purpose-built transport interchanges, such as {{metro|Four Lane Ends}}, [[Heworth Interchange|Heworth]] and {{metro|Regent Centre}} were built for this purpose. Integration was short-lived, and lasted until the [[Bus deregulation|deregulation]] of bus services, in 1986.<ref name=\"CLmetrohistory\">{{cite news|last=Meechan|first=Simon|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/history/how-tyne-wear-metro-made-12031209|title=How the Tyne and Wear Metro was made - we go back 36 years to the very beginning|date=16 October 2016|newspaper=ChronicleLive|access-date=15 June 2019|url-status=live|publisher=|location=}}</ref> It is, however, still possible to purchase [[Transfare]] tickets, in order to combine a journey made using multiple modes of transport in Tyne and Wear.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/adult-transfare|title=Adult Transfare|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tyne and Wear and Tees Rail Map.svg|thumb|600px|center|A map of commuter rail services in the region, including Tyne and Wear Metro services.]]\n\n==Expansion and growth==\n\n=== Extension to Newcastle Airport ===\nIn November 1991, the Tyne and Wear Metro was extended to [[Newcastle International Airport|Newcastle Airport]] \u2013 at a cost of \u00a312 million.<ref name=\":7\" /> The new section of track, covering a distance of around {{convert|2.2|mi|km|abbr=}}, continued along the alignment of the former [[Ponteland Railway]], with two purpose-built stations constructed at [[Callerton Parkway Metro station|Callerton Parkway]] and [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]].<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /><ref name=\"LRTAHLR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lrta.org/mrthistory.html|title=The History of Tramways and Evolution of Light Rail|last=|first=|date=|website=Light Rail Transit Association|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Extension to Wearside ===\nIn March 2002, a \u00a3100&nbsp;million extension, covering {{convert|11.5|mi|km|abbr=}}, was opened from {{metro|Pelaw}} to [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]] and {{metro|South Hylton}}.<ref name=\":8\" /> The extension used part of the existing [[Durham Coast Line]], with the line being adapted in order to allow a shared service between Metro and rail services \u2013 therefore becoming the first system in the [[United Kingdom]] to implement a form of the [[Karlsruhe model]].<ref name=\"railwaytechnology\" /> Between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]], intermediate stations at [[Brockley Whins Metro station|Brockley Whins]], [[East Boldon Metro station|East Boldon]] and [[Seaburn Metro station|Seaburn]] were re-built, with a further three being purpose-built for the network, at [[Fellgate Metro station|Fellgate]], [[Stadium of Light Metro station|Stadium of Light]] and [[St Peter's Metro station|St. Peter's]]. Between [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]] and {{metro|South Hylton}}, around {{convert|3|mi|km|abbr=}} of the former [[Durham\u2013Sunderland line|Durham and Sunderland Railway]], which closed to passenger traffic in May 1964, was used as the alignment of the route. Five purpose-built stations at [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane]], [[University Metro station|University]], [[Millfield Metro station|Millfield]], [[Pallion Metro station|Pallion]] and [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]] were constructed for the network.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/p/penshaw_first/|title=Penshaw Station (1st site)|last=|first=|date=|website=Disused Stations|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Upgrades and development ==\n\n=== Project Orpheus ===\nIn 2002, Nexus unveiled an ambitious 15 year plan for transport in Tyne and Wear, named ''Project Orpheus''. The project, valued at \u00a31.5 billion, aimed to extend the existing Metro network, including links to [[Cramlington]], [[Doxford Park]], [[Killingworth]], [[MetroCentre (shopping centre)|Metrocentre]], [[Seaham]], [[Team Valley]] and [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]]. In addition to this, plans would see the introduction of street-running [[Tram|trams]], [[Water taxi|river buses]] across the [[River Tyne|Tyne]], and [[Aerial lift|cable cars]], linking 29 key corridors.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/1993003.stm|title=Tram rides for Tyneside|date=2002-05-17|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-18|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/2568997.stm|title=Trams closer for Tyne and Wear|date=2002-12-12|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-18|url-status=live|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/road-tram-plan-stuck-amber-1628673|title=Road tram plan stuck on amber|last=|first=|date=2004-08-26|website=ChronicleLive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> The project has since been abandoned, with plans reworked and developed into the ''Metro: All Change'' programme.\n\n=== Metro: All Change ===\n\n==== Phase 1 ====\nThe first phase of Metro's ''All Change'' programme saw the start of a \u00a325 million project to install new ticket machines at all 60 stations across the network. Unlike the former ticket machines, which only accepted payment with coins, the new machines are able to accept payment with credit and debit card (with an upgrade to accept [[contactless payment]] in 2013),<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metro-passengers-feel-benefit-contactless-payment|title=Metro passengers feel the benefit of contactless payment|last=|first=|date=13 January 2014|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> notes and coins.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-16126081|title=Revamp for Metro ticket machines|date=2011-12-11|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-17|language=en-GB}}</ref> Automated ticket barriers (at 13 stations), and smart card validators at all stations across the network were also introduced, as part of the first phase of the ''All Change'' programme.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/city-metro-stations-get-new-smart-ticket-machines-and-gates|title=City Metro stations get new smart ticket machines and gates|last=|first=|date=22 October 2012|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/pop-card-validators-metro-stations-are-put-through-their-paces|title=Pop card validators at Metro stations are put through their paces|last=|first=|date=21 March 2013|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first phase of the programme also saw the completion of a new station at [[Simonside Metro station|Simonside]], in March 2008,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Rail-News/Nexus-announces-new-Metro-station|title=Nexus announces new Metro station|last=|first=|date=7 March 2008|website=Rail Technology Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> as well as the refurbishment and modernisation of [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], in 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-invest-%C2%A340m-metro-modernisation-over-next-12-months|title=Nexus to invest \u00a340m in Metro modernisation over the next 12 months|last=|first=|date=17 June 2015|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> An upgrade of platforms at [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]], and the refurbishment and modernisation of several other stations was also undertaken during this phase. Lifts and escalators have also been replaced at several stations, between 2009 and 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-completes-%C2%A31m-metro-lift-replacement-project|title=Nexus completes \u00a31m Metro lift replacement project|last=|first=|date=10 December 2009|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metro-says-goodbye-its-last-original-escalator|title=Metro says goodbye to its last original escalator|last=|first=|date=23 March 2016|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/new-escalators-city-centre-metro-stations|title=New escalators for city centre Metro stations|last=|first=|date=26 April 2012|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> Phase 1 of the programme also involved the overhaul of infrastructure, including communications, track and overhead power lines, structures and embankments.\n\n==== Phase 2 ====\nPhase 2 of the ''All Change'' programme saw the \u00a320 million refurbishment of 86 [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]] (originally all 90 [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]] were due to be refurbished). Each [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocar]] was stripped down to its frame and built back up again, with the addition of improved disabled access, new door control systems, and renewed interiors, seating and lighting. A new cadmium yellow and black livery was also adopted. Work commenced in June 2010, at [[Wabtec Corporation|Wabtec]] in [[Doncaster]], and was completed five months ahead of schedule, in August 2015.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metrocar-takes-road-%C2%A320m-refurbishment-begins|title=Metrocar takes to road as \u00a320m refurbishment begins|last=|first=|date=22 June 2010|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/tyne-and-wear-metro-fleet-refurbishment-complete/41205.article|title=Tyne & Wear Metro fleet refurbishment complete|last=|first=|date=3 August 2015|website=Railway Gazette International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"RTM2014\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/wabtec-awarded-tyne-and-wear-metro-refurbishment-contract/35059.article|title=Wabtec awarded Tyne & Wear Metro refurbishment contract|last=|first=|date=11 June 2010|website=Railway Gazette International|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> The first [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocar]] to receive refurbishment was 4041, the unit being named after former Gateshead Councillor and MP, [[Harry Cowans]], in honour of his work in the 1970s, to help to secure the construction of the network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/first-refurbished-metro-train-re-dedicated|title=First refurbished Metro train re-dedicated|last=|first=|date=31 October 2011|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe second phase of the programme also saw the modernisation of a further 45 stations, including the re-building of the station at [[North Shields metro station|North Shields]], which was completed in September 2012,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metro-line-re-opens-wallsend-tynemouth|title=Metro line re-opens Wallsend-Tynemouth|last=|first=|date=2 September 2012|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> as well as the installation of new communications system, and the overhaul and maintenance of structures such as bridges, tunnels, track and overhead power lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-starts-biggest-engineering-project-metro-system-was-built|title=Nexus starts biggest engineering project on Metro since the system was built|last=|first=|date=10 March 2011|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Phase 3 ====\nThe third phase of Metro's ''All Change'' programme began in 2019, with the procurement of a new fleet of 46 (originally 42) units, designed by [[Switzerland|Swiss]] manufacturer, [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]]. Delivery of the new rolling stock will commence towards the end of 2021, with all units introduced in to passenger service by 2024 \u2013 replacing the current fleet of [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]].<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/modes/stadler-to-build-tyne-and-wear-metro-fleet/55643.article|title=Stadler to build Tyne & Wear metro fleet|last=|first=|date=28 January 2020|website=Railway Gazette International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-and-stadler-officially-sign-contract-new-metro-train-fleet|title=Nexus and Stadler officially sign the contract for a new Metro train fleet|last=|first=|date=11 February 2020|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> It will also see the introduction of a new signalling system, overhaul and maintenance of structures, track and overhead lines, and further station improvements.\n\n=== Maintenance and Renewals Skills Centre ===\nIn July 2018, Nexus announced the beginning of work to construct the new Maintenance and Renewals Skills Centre, at Mile End Road in [[South Shields]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/work-starts-ps84m-nexus-learning-centre-south-shields|title=Work starts on \u00a38.4m Nexus Learning Centre in South Shields|last=|first=|date=24 July 2018|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-ps84m-rail-training-centre-south-shields-gets-green-light|title=Nexus' \u00a38.4m rail training centre in South Shields gets the green light|last=|first=|date=22 March 2018|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-build-ps84m-rail-training-centre-south-shields|title=Nexus to build \u00a38.4m rail training centre in South Shields|last=|first=|date=28 November 2017|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> The \u00a38.4 million project will see the construction of a three-storey training centre, with classrooms, a mock control room, driver training simulator, covered tracks and inspection pits, and a mock Metro station, as well as a {{convert|70|m|ft|abbr=on}} stretch of dual track, to be used to carry out infrastructure training, including track, points, signalling and overhead line. The site will also be used to stable and maintain a small number of vehicles.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gallifordtry.co.uk/news/news-centre/galliford-try-appointed-to-tyneside-rail-project/|title=Galliford Try appointed to Tyneside rail project|last=|first=|date=28 November 2017|website=Galliford Try|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Metro Flow ===\nIn March 2020, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] announced a \u00a3103 million scheme, known as ''Metro Flow'', during the 2020 [[Budget of the United Kingdom|Budget]]. The project aims to increase frequency from 5 to 6 trains per hour, reduce journey times and improve service reliability. From September 2022, the project will see three sections of single line between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Bede Metro station|Bede]] converted to dual use, with an existing freight-only line electrified, and re-designed to operate using a similar system to the shared line between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]]. As part of the project, four additional [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] units have been funded, bringing the total number of units on order from 42 to 46.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/our-ps100m-project-boost-frequency-and-reliability-metro|title=Our \u00a3100m project to boost frequency and reliability on Metro|last=|first=|date=11 March 2020|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/uk/rail-in-the-2020-budget/55997.article|title=Rail in the 2020 budget|last=|first=|date=11 March 2020|website=Railway Gazette International|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Service and frequency==\n\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro network consists of two lines:\n\n*'''Green Line:''' [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]] to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]]\n*'''Yellow Line:''' [[South Shields Metro station|South Shields]] to [[St. James Metro station|St. James]] via [[Whitley Bay Metro station|Whitley Bay]]\n\nServices commence between 05:00 and 06:00 (between 06:00 and 07:00 on Sunday), with frequent trains running until around midnight. Each line runs up to every 12 minutes during the day (Monday to Saturday), and up to every 15 minutes during the evening and on Sunday. This allows for a combined frequency of up to every 6 minutes (Monday to Saturday), and up to every 7\u20138 minutes during the evening and on Sunday, between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]]  and [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]]. Additional trains run during morning and evening peak hours (Monday to Friday) between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Regent Centre Interchange|Regent Centre]] or [[Monkseaton Metro station|Monkseaton]]. This provides a Metro up to every 3 minutes between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]], at peak times. Originally, there was also a Red Line between Heworth (later Pelaw) and Benton and a Blue Line between St James and North Shields. Additional trains ran on these lines during peak hours to increase the frequency at the busier stations.<ref name=\"SRT23\"/>\n{|\n|-\n|{{TWM Green line RDT}}{{nb5}}{{TWM Yellow line RDT}}\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n== Fleet and operations ==\n===Control Centre===\nThe Metro Control Centre is based at [[Gosforth]], in a building alongside the station at [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]]. It is responsible for operating the network's signalling and electrical supply, as well as being used to communicate with train drivers and other staff, using two-way radio equipment.<ref name=\":9\" /> The original equipment at the control centre was replaced in 2007,<ref name=\"railwaytechnology\" /> with a new computerised signalling control system installed in August 2018, at a cost of \u00a312 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.railway-technology.com/news/nexus-modernise-tyne-wear-metro-control-room-uk/|title=Nexus to modernise Tyne and Wear Metro control room in UK|date=2018-07-16|website=Railway Technology|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nexus.org.uk/news/item/watch-timelapse-video-ps12m-metro-control-room-revamp|title=Watch: timelapse video of \u00a312m Metro control room revamp|last=|first=|date=21 August 2018|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Depots===\n{{main|South Gosforth TMD}}\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro is currently operated from a single depot, also based in [[Gosforth]]. The depot opened in 1923, by the [[London and North Eastern Railway]], and was used to house the former [[Tyneside Electrics|''Tyneside Electrics'']] stock. The depot was inherited by Metro, prior to the system's opening in August 1980.<ref name=\"gosdep\">{{cite web|url=http://thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/stations/Gosforth_depot|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Stations: Gosforth depot|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref> The depot is located at the centre of the triangular fork between the branch to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]], and the northern leg of the [[North Tyneside Loop]]. It is situated between stations at [[Longbenton Metro station|Longbenton]], [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]] and [[Regent Centre Interchange|Regent Centre]], and is used for stabling, cleaning, maintenance and repair of the fleet. It can be accessed by trains from either east or west, and there is also a depot-avoiding line running from east to west, which is not used in public service. \n\nPrior to the arrival of new rolling stock towards the end of 2021, a new depot is currently being constructed near [[Howdon]], in [[North Tyneside]]. The site will be used as a temporary stabling and maintenance facility for up to 10 [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Metrocars]], whilst the current depot at [[South Gosforth TMD|South Gosforth]] is reconfigured. The temporary depot at [[Howdon]] is expected to open during summer 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/work-starts-temporary-metro-depot-north-tyneside|title=Work starts on a temporary Metro depot in North Tyneside|last=|first=|date=11 July 2019|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/temporary-metro-depot-takes-shape-north-tyneside|title=Temporary Metro depot takes shape in North Tyneside|last=|first=|date=2 January 2020|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> A further vehicle stabling and maintenance facility is also scheduled to open in [[South Tyneside]], as part of the Maintenance and Renewals Skills Centre at [[South Shields]].<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n=== Current fleet ===\n{{main|Tyne & Wear Metrocars}}\nSince the Tyne and Wear Metro opened in 1980, it has operated using the same rolling stock. The fleet comprises a total of 89 (originally 90) articulated units, known as [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|''Metrocars'']], which are numbered 4001\u20134090. When in service, Metrocars are normally coupled together in pairs, and have a maximum speed of {{convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. The first units to be built were two prototypes, numbered 4001 and 4002, which were delivered for testing in 1975. These were followed by 88 production units, which were built between 1978 and 1981. The design of the Metrocar was based on the [[Stadtbahnwagen B]], a [[Germany|German]] [[light rail]] vehicle developed in the early 1970s. The units were built by [[Metro-Cammell]], [[Washwood Heath]].<ref name=\"TTMtrains\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/trains/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Trains|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/tyne-wear-metro-celebrates-40th-9363207|title=Tyne and Wear Metro celebrates its 40th birthday with a special journey|last=Southern|first=Keiran|date=31 May 2015|website=ChronicleLive|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SRT\" />\n\nThe fleet has been refurbished several times, and several liveries have been used. The original livery used at opening was cadmium yellow and white, in accordance with the colours used by the [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive]] at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tynesideheritagevehicles.co.uk/our_vehicles/group_vehicles/uvk290t.html|title=290 / UVK 290T|last=|first=|date=|website=Tyneside Heritage Vehicles|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref> A mid-life refurbishment of the fleet, carried out in-house, took place between 1995 and 2000, and a new livery was adopted consisting of red, green or blue bodies, with yellow front and rear ends, and triangles containing the ''Metro'' logo on the doors.<ref name=\"TTMtrains\" /><ref name=\"RTM2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Interviews/bringing-contracts-back-in-house|title=Bringing contracts back in-house|last=|first=|date=14 March 2014|website=Rail Technology Magazine|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"railwaytechnology\" />\n\nA \u00a320 million refurbishment of 86 Metrocars (originally all 90 were due to be refurbished) began in June 2010, with the goal of the refurbishment programme being to extend the service life of until 2025, prior to the delivery of new rolling stock. Each Metrocar was stripped down to its frame and built back up again, with the addition of improved disabled access, new door control systems, and renewed interiors, seating and lighting. A new black, grey and yellow livery was also adopted.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/new-metro-train-colours-revealed|title=New Metro train colours revealed|last=|first=|date=7 October 2011|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Refurbishment work was completed five months ahead of schedule, in August 2015.<ref name=\"RTM2014\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Branding and livery\n|width=215 |height=165\n|align=center\n|footer=\n|File:Tynemouth station, with Metro train, 1980, geograph-5317028-by-Walter-Dendy,-deceased.jpg\n |alt1=1980-1990s\n |1980\u20131990s|File:Tyne and Wear Metro No 4064, Tanners Bank, Tynemouth, 24 May 2012.jpg\n |alt2=1990s-2010s\n |1990s\u20132010s|File:Metro train at South Shields (16873964346).jpg\n |alt3=2010s-present \n |2010s\u2013present}}\n\n===Future fleet===\nIn 2016, Nexus unveiled plans to secure funding of \u00a3550 million for a replacement fleet, with a target for them to be in service by the early 2020s.<ref name=\"CLMETRO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/1bn-plan-improve-metro-approved-11637441|title=\u00a31bn plan to improve the Metro approved by North East transport chiefs|last=O'Donoghue|first=Dan|date=20 July 2016|website=ChronicleLive|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref> In November 2017, [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Philip Hammond]] announced that the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] would contribute \u00a3337 million towards the new fleet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://netimesmagazine.co.uk/editorial/budget-provides-transport-boost-tyne-wear/|title=Budget provides transport boost for Tyne & Wear|last=|first=|date=30 November 2017|website=North East Times|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref> The proposed new fleet was planned to have dual voltage capability, able to operate on the Metro's existing 1.5 kV [[Direct current|DC]] electrification system, as well as the 25 kV [[Alternating current|AC]] used on the [[Network Rail]] network, to allow for expansion of Metro service. [[Battery (electricity)|Battery]] technology was considered.<ref name=\"Sundechoextend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/news/metro-bosses-unveil-plans-to-extend-network-including-direct-link-between-sunderland-and-south-tyneside-1-8016661|title=Metro bosses unveil plans to extend network, including direct link between Sunderland and South Tyneside|last=|first=|date=15 July 2016|website=Sunderland Echo|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"GRN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalrailnews.com/2016/07/20/new-trains-and-expanded-network-put-forward-in-tyne-and-wear-metro-strategy/|title=New trains and expanded network put forward in Tyne and Wear Metro strategy|last=|first=|date=20 July 2016|website=Rail Engineer|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Rmagnewfleet\">{{cite book|last1=Pickering|first1=Graeme|title=Metro's new fleet receives the green light|publisher=[[Rail (magazine)|Rail Magazine]]|year=2017|isbn=|edition=6\u201319 December|location=|pages=62\u201367}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]], [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]], a [[Downer Rail]]/[[CRRC]] joint venture, [[Hitachi]] and [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] were short-listed to build the new fleet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/screenshot/https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/five-bidders-invited-negotiate-build-new-metro-fleet|title=Five bidders invited to negotiate to build a new Metro fleet|last=|first=|date=17 September 2018|website=Nexus|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131201847/https://web.archive.org/screenshot/https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/five-bidders-invited-negotiate-build-new-metro-fleet|archive-date=31 January 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Five shortlisted for new Tyne & Wear Metro fleet \u2013 contract worth \u00a3362m|date=2018|work=The Railway Magazine|access-date=|url-status=live|issue=1411|page=10}}</ref> [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] was awarded a contract to build and maintain 42 five carriage [[light rail]] vehicles in January 2020, with deliveries to commence in late 2021, and all trains to be in passenger service by 2024. The new trains will feature next stop audio-visual information displays, [[London Underground|Tube]]-style linear seating to increase capacity, wider doors and aisles, air conditioning, WiFi and charging points.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-51277602 Tyne and Wear Metro: Swiss firm Stadler to build new fleet] ''BBC News'' 28 January 2020</ref> Following the announcement of the \u00a3103 million ''Metro Flow'' project, in March 2020, four additional [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] units have been funded, bringing the total number of units on order from 42 to 46.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|width=800 |height=80\n|align=center\n|Tyne & Wear Metro New Stock w-pantograph.png|alt1=New rolling stock\n |Concept art of The new Tyne and Wear Metro rolling stock, built by [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]].}}\n\n===Ancillary vehicles===\nIn addition to passenger trains, the Tyne and Wear Metro also operate three battery-electric locomotives (numbered BL1\u2013BL3), which were manufactured by [[Hunslet Engine Company|Hunslet]] in 1988. As well as this, the company also operate a [[Plasser & Theurer|Plasser and Theurer]] ballast tamper, and 15 wagons, which are used for maintenance and repair work.\n\n== Ownership ==\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro is publicly owned, receiving funding from council tax payers and government. [[Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|Nexus]], which owns and manages the Metro, contracted out operations and train maintenance as part of a deal with the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]], in order to secure modernisation investment and operating subsidy for the system between 2010 and 2021. Nexus continued to set fares, frequency of services and operating hours. Opponents would suggest that this was privatisation by the back door, though some services had already been contracted out, such as cleaning of stations and ticket inspections. \n\nIn November 2008, Nexus invited potential bidders to declare an interest in a contract to run the operations side of the business on its behalf. The successful bidder was to obtain a seven-year contract commencing on 1 April 2010, with up to an additional two years depending on performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/news/2010/nexus-names-final-two-bidders-metro-operations-contract|title=Nexus names final two bidders for Metro operations contract|date=2 October 2009|publisher=Nexus|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> In February 2009, four bids were shortlisted: [[DB Regio]], [[MTR Corporation]], [[Serco-Abellio]], and an in-house bid from Nexus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/7864519.stm|title=Foreign bids for Metro contract|date=2 February 2009|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=3 February 2009}}</ref> By October 2009, the shortlist had been reduced to bids from DB Regio and Nexus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/tyne/8288315.stm|title=Final shortlist for Metro service|date=3 October 2009|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=3 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, DB Regio was named as the preferred bidder, with the contract for operating the system signed in February 2010, and the handover of the service taking place in April 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|date=3 December 2009|title=DB Regio preferred bidder for Tyne & Wear Metro operating contract|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/10/db-regio-preferred-bidder-for-tyne-metro-operating-contract.html|journal=[[Railway Gazette International]]}}</ref><ref name=\"nexusfeb3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/news/2010/%C2%A3580-million-funding-gives-metro-world-class-future|title=\u00a3580 Million Funding Gives Metro a World-Class Future|last=|first=|date=3 February 2010|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=27 November 2010}}</ref> One of DB Regio's first initiatives was the ''Metro Dig It'' programme, and involved the re-painting of stations and deep-cleaning of stations and trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro-dig-it.co.uk|title=Metro - Dig It!|last=|first=|date=|website=Metro - Dig It!|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403131658/http://www.metro-dig-it.co.uk/|archivedate=3 April 2010|accessdate=31 March 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In February 2010, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] confirmed it would award Nexus up to \u00a3580 million to modernise and operate the Tyne and Wear Metro, with up to \u00a3350 million to be spent on the ''Metro: All Change'' programme, over the course of the following eleven years. A further \u00a3230 million would support running and maintenance costs, over the following nine years.<ref name=\"nexusfeb3\" />\n\nIn March 2016, Nexus announced that they did not intend to renew the contract with DB Regio, following the contract ending in 2017, after stating that they were dissatisfied with the operator due to missed performance targets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/frustrated-metro-delays-youre-right-12105683|title=Frustrated by Metro delays? You're right to be \u2013 report reveals string of missed targets|last=|first=|date=|website=ChronicleLive|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=6 April 2017}}</ref> In April 2017, Nexus took over direct operation of the system for a planned period of two years, with the intention to re-tender the contract. The [[National Union of Rail, Maritime and Transport Workers|RMT]] trade union, however, has argued that the direct operation should be made permanent, and operation of the system should remain in public ownership.<ref name=\"Conend\" /><ref name=\"Metpublic\" /> As of March 2020, the Tyne and Wear Metro network is still under public ownership, with services operated by Nexus.\n\n== Infrastructure ==\n===Stations===\n{{See also|List of Tyne and Wear Metro stations}}\n\nThe 60 stations on the Tyne and Wear Metro network vary widely in character. Some are former [[British Rail]] stations, whilst others were purpose-built for the Metro. Most of the stations are above ground, but several in central [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[Gateshead]] are underground, namely [[Central Station Metro station|Central]], {{metro|Jesmond}}, {{metro|Haymarket}}, {{metro|Monument}}, {{metro|Manors}}, [[St James Metro station|St. James]] and [[Gateshead Interchange|Gateshead]]. In [[Sunderland]], [[Park Lane Interchange|Park Lane]] and {{stn|Sunderland}} stations also have underground platforms.<ref name=\"TTstations2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/stations/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Stations|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref> Four of the stations on the network, Central, Heworth, Manors and Sunderland, allow for interchange with [[National Rail]] services. {{stn|Sunderland}} is unique, in that it is the only station in the [[United Kingdom where [[Light rail|light]] and [[heavy rail]] services use the same platforms.\n\nGenerally, all Metro stations are unstaffed, with the exception of the underground stations, and gated stations when the ticket barriers are closed. All stations are equipped with ticket machines, shelters and seating, next train information displays, and emergency help points.<ref name=\"TTstations\" /> Ticket machines are able to accept payment with credit and debit card (including [[contactless payment]]), notes and coins.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":12\" /> Automated ticket barriers (at 13 stations), and smart card validators at all stations, were also installed during the first phase of Metro's ''All Change'' programme.<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":14\" /> Despite the majority of stations being open to access, the Tyne and Wear Metro has the third-highest level of passenger income per year (\u00a345.2 million in 2013/2014) of the eight [[light rail]] networks in [[England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/320645/light-rail-and-tram-statistics-2013-14.pdf|title=Light Rail and Tram Statistics: England 2013/14|last=|first=|date=17 June 2014|website=Department for Transport|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Regular checks are made by patrols of inspectors, both at stations and on board trains. Passengers caught travelling on the Metro without a ticket are subject to a \u00a320 [[penalty fare]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro/tickets/penalty-fares|title=Penalty Fares|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Stations\n|width=215 |height=165\n|align=center\n|1=File:Haymarket Metro station, 20 September 2010 (4).jpg|2=[[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], the first underground Metro station to be refurbished, branded in the new corporate colour scheme.|5=St Peter's Metro station, 8 September 2006.jpg|6=[[St Peter's Metro station|St. Peter's]], a purpose-built station, constructed in the early 2000s, following the Metro's extension to [[Wearside]].|7=Wansbeck Road Metro station, Tyne & Wear (geograph 4254512).jpg|8=[[Wansbeck Road Metro station|Wansbeck Road]], a purpose-built station, which opened in May 1981, following the Metro's extension to [[Bank Foot Metro station|Bank Foot]].|9=Metro Station, Whitley Bay - geograph.org.uk - 1707495.jpg|10=[[Whitley Bay Metro station|Whitley Bay]], one of the network's former [[British Rail]] stations, located on the [[North Tyneside Loop]].}}\n\n=== Bicycles ===\nMost stations on the network have cycle racks, with smart cycle lockers located at 21 stations across the network (as of March 2020).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/cycle/cycle-lockers|title=Cycle lockers|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Following a trial period in 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/metro-holds-limited-trial-allowing-people-travel-non-folding-bikes|title=Metro holds limited trial allowing people to travel with non-folding bikes|last=|first=|date=30 March 2016|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> non-folding bicycles are permitted to travel on Metro between 10:00 and 15:00 and after 19:00 on weekdays, and all day at weekends, between [[Callerton Parkway Metro station|Callerton Parkway]] or [[Manors Metro station|Manors]] and [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], and between [[Gateshead Stadium Metro station|Gateshead Stadium]] and [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]] or [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]]. Non-folding bicycles are not permitted to travel between [[Callerton Parkway Metro station|Callerton Parkway]] and [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]], or between [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]] and [[Gateshead Stadium Metro station|Gateshead Stadium]] at any time. Folding bicycles are permitted to travel without restriction, across the entire Metro network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nexus.org.uk/cycle/bikes-metro-trial|title=Bikes on Metro trial|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/metro/looking-after-our-passengers/bikes-metro|title=Bikes on Metro|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Tunnels ===\n[[File:TWM tunnels.png|thumb|A map of the network in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] and [[Gateshead]]. Metro routes are shown in red, with dotted red lines displaying tunnel sections.]]\nUnder [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], two routes run underground at right angles to each other, and intersect at [[Monument Metro station|Monument]], which has four platforms on two levels. The first route, shared by both the Green Line (from [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]] to [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]]) and Yellow Line (from [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]] to [[St James Metro station|St. James]]), runs from north to south. It heads underground at [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], and runs south through {{metro|Haymarket}}, [[Monument Metro station|Monument]] and [[Central Station Metro station|Central]], before rising above ground to cross the [[Queen Elizabeth II Bridge, Newcastle upon Tyne|Queen Elizabeth II Bridge]] over the [[River Tyne]]. It then enters another tunnel, running underneath [[Gateshead]], serving [[Gateshead Interchange|Gateshead]], before rising above ground again before the station at [[Gateshead Stadium Metro station|Gateshead Stadium]].<ref name=\"TTPELGOS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/pelaw-gosforth/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro: Routes : Pelaw \u2013 Gosforth|last=|first=|date=|website=TheTrams|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe second underground route, part of the Yellow Line (from [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]] to [[St James Metro station|St. James]]), runs from east to west, heading underground after running east alongside the [[East Coast Main Line]], before serving [[Manors Metro station|Manors]] and [[Monument Metro station|Monument]], then terminating at [[St James Metro station|St. James]].<ref name=\"TTNTL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/tyneandwear/tynecoastloop/|title=Tyne and Wear Metro : Routes : North Tyneside Loop|publisher=TheTrams|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref> Yellow Line trains pass through [[Monument Metro station|Monument]] twice, once eastbound through the east-west platforms, and then, after running around the [[North Tyneside Loop]], southbound through the north-south platforms before running to [[South Shields Interchange|South Shields]].<ref name=\"TAGBI\"/>\n\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro is one of the few rapid transit systems in the world with a [[pretzel|''pretzel'']] configuration, in which a line crosses over itself and trains pass through the same station twice at different platforms. This arrangement also exists at [[Voorweg RandstadRail station|Voorweg]] on the [[Randstadrail|RandstadRail]] network in [[The Hague]], and at [[Serdika Metro Station|Serdika]], on the [[Sofia Metro]] in [[Bulgaria]].\n\nA short spur line, running partly under a tunnel, runs from [[Manors Metro station|Manors]] to [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]]. The line is used for empty stock movements only, and has no passenger service. Before the Metro tunnels were created, it was part of the main rail route to [[Newcastle railway station|Newcastle]], and connected to the main line at [[Manors railway station|Manors]].<ref name=\"TTPELGOS\" />\n\nThe tunnels were constructed in the late 1970s, using mining techniques, and were constructed as single-track tubes with a diameter of {{convert|4.75|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"TAGBI\" /> The tunnels under [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] were mechanically bored through [[boulder clay]], and lined with cast iron or concrete segments. The tunnel under [[Gateshead]] was bored through [[sandstone]] and excavated coal seams. Old coal mine workings, some of which dated from the [[Middle Ages]], had to be filled in before the tunnelling began.<ref name=\":9\" /> \n\n===Distances===\nDistances on the system are measured from a datum point at [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/tw_metro_station_distances|title=TW Metro Station Distances - a Freedom of Information request to Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|date=2013-01-18|website=WhatDoTheyKnow|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> The system is metric, with distances in kilometres, and rounded to the nearest metre. Lines are designated ''In'' and ''Out''. The ''In'' line runs from [[St James Metro station|St. James]] to [[South Shields Metro station|South Shields]] via the ''inside'' of the [[North Tyneside Loop]] (via [[Wallsend Metro station|Wallsend]] then [[Whitley Bay Metro station|Whitley Bay]]), with the ''Out'' line running in the opposite direction. By extension, the ''In'' line runs from [[Newcastle Airport Metro station|Airport]] to [[South Gosforth Metro station|South Gosforth]], and from [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] to [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]].\n\nDistance plates are mounted on all [[Overhead lines#Overhead catenary|overhead line]] structures. Different distances are normally quoted for stations, depending on whether the direction of travel is ''In'' or ''Out''. Distances increase from the datum in all directions.<ref name=\"Maxey\">{{cite book|last=Maxey|first=David|title=Mile by Mile: Rail Mileages of Britain and Ireland|publisher=Peter Watts Publishing Limited|year=1987|isbn=9780906025444|location=Woodchester|pages=}}</ref> The part of line between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]] owned by [[Network Rail]] is dual-marked in both metric units, as well as miles and chains. The boundary between the two systems is located at Pelaw Junction.<ref name=\"Quail2\">{{cite book|last=Jacobs|first=Gerald|title=Railway Track Diagrams Book 2: Eastern|publisher=Trackmaps|year=2006|isbn=9780954986629|location=|pages=|coauthors=}}</ref> The closest adjacent stations by distance on the network are [[St Peter's Metro station|St. Peter's]] and [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]], with the furthest apart being [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Fellgate Metro station|Fellgate]].\n\n===Electrification===\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro is electrified with [[overhead lines]] at [[railway electrification in Great Britain#1,500 V DC, overhead|1,500 V DC]], and is now the only rail network in the [[United Kingdom]] to use this system.<ref name=railwaytechnology /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azocleantech.com/article.aspx?ArticleID=262|title=Are Electric Trains Eco-Friendly?|publisher=AZO Clean Tech|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref> Nexus have stated that their long term ambition is to convert the electrification of the line between [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[Sunderland station|Sunderland]], which is shared with [[heavy rail]], to the [[Network Rail]] standard of [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25\u00a0kV AC]]. However, in doing this, a new fleet of dual voltage trains would be required.<ref name=\"Sundechoextend\"/><ref name=\"GRN\"/>\n\n==Ridership==\nDuring the 1985/86 financial year, the Tyne and Wear Metro carried a total of 59.1 million passengers \u2013 the highest figure it has ever achieved. By 1987/88, this had declined to 44.9 million. The decline was attributed to the loss of integration with bus services, following [[Bus deregulation in Great Britain|deregulation]] in 1986, as well as the general decline in public transport use in the area.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\"dftjour\">{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/719478/lrt0101.ods|title=Table LRT0101: Passenger journeys on light rail and trams by system: England - annual from 1983/84|last=|first=|date=14 June 2019|website=Department for Transport|publisher=|format=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=}}</ref> Usage continued to decline during the 1990s, reaching its lowest level during 2000/01. Since the turn of the century, passenger usage has risen and stabilised, fluctuating in a range of 35\u201340 million passengers annually. Prior to 2016/17, the Tyne and Wear Metro consistently ranked as the second-most used [[tram]] and [[light rail]] network in the [[United Kingdom]], after [[London]]'s [[Docklands Light Railway]]. The Metro is now ranked as the third-most used [[tram]] and [[light rail]] network in the [[United Kingdom]], after the [[Docklands Light Railway]], closely following the [[Manchester Metrolink]].<ref name=\"dftjour\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/809958/lrt9903.ods|title=Table LRT9903a: Edinburgh Trams statistics, annual from 2014/15|last=|first=|date=19 June 2019|website=Department for Transport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/852322/lrt9902.ods|title=Table LRT9902a: Glasgow Underground statistics, annual from 1982/83|last=|first=|date=|website=Department for Transport|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n | width=500\n | height=250\n | xAxisTitle=Year\n | yAxisTitle=Passenger journeys (million)\n | legend=Operator\n | type=line\n | x= 1984, 1985, 1986, 1987, 1988, 1989, 1990, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019\n| y1 = 6.2, 6.0, 6.2, 6.2, 5.4, 5.4, 5.6, 5.8, 5.0, 5.2, 5.5, 5.4, 4.9, 4.9, 4.7, 4.4, 4.3, 4.1, 4.9, 4.5, 3.7, 3.9, 3.6, 3.4, 2.9, 2.3, 2.2, 1.6, 1.1, 3.7, 4.3, 4.1, 4.9, 5.1, 5.2, 5.2\n| y2 = {{repeat|31|, }} 4.1, 5.3, 5.8, 7.5, 7.5\n| y3 = 12.3, 12.7, 13.1, 13.7, 13.6, 13.6, 13.5, 13.7, 13.6, 13.5, 14.3, 14.7, 14.3, 13.7, 14.1, 14.6, 14.7, 14.4, 13.8, 13.4, 13.3, 13.3, 13.2, 13.5, 14.5, 14.1, 13.1, 13.0, 12.9, 12.6, 12.7, 13.0, 11.4, 11.1, 13.1, 13.1\n| y4 = {{repeat|9|, }} 8.1, 11.3, 12.3, 12.6, 13.4, 13.8, 13.2, 14.2, 17.2, 18.2, 18.8, 18.9, 19.7, 19.9, 19.8, 20.0, 21.1, 19.6, 19.2, 22.3, 25.0, 29.2, 31.2, 34.3, 37.8, 41.2, 43.7\n| y5 = {{repeat|16|, }} 4.8, 5.4, 4.8, 4.9, 5.1, 5.0, 5.1, 4.9, 4.8, 4.7, 4.7, 4.8, 4.9, 4.8, 4.7, 4.4, 4.8, 6.2, 5.7, 5.9\n| y6 = {{repeat|20|, }} 0.4, 8.5, 9.8, 10.1, 10.2, 9.8, 9.0, 9.7, 9.0, 7.4, 7.9, 8.1, 12.2, 16.4, 17.8, 18.8\n| y7 = {{repeat|11|, }} 2.2, 5.3, 7.8, 9.2, 10.4, 10.9, 11.1, 11.4, 11.5, 12.3, 12.8, 13.1, 14.0, 14.8, 15.0, 14.7, 15.0, 15.0, 14.4, 12.6, 11.5, 11.6, 12.6, 12.3, 11.9\n| y8 = 49.8, 57.2, 59.1, 46.4, 44.9, 45.4, 45.5, 43.6, 40.6, 38.9, 38.3, 37, 35.9, 35.4, 35, 33.8, 32.7, 32.5, 33.4, 36.6, 37.9, 36.8, 35.8, 37.9, 39.8, 40.6, 40.8, 39.9, 37.9, 37, 35.7, 38.1, 40.3, 37.7, 36.4, 36.4\n | y1Title=Blackpool Tramway\n | y2Title=Edinburgh Trams\n | y3Title=Glasgow Subway\n | y4Title=Manchester Metrolink\n | y5Title=West Midland Metro\n | y6Title=Nottingham Express Transit\n | y7Title=Sheffield Supertram\n | y8Title=Tyne and Wear Metro\n | colors=#5f195e, #b31b1b, #c26b00, #ffdb4e, #0075bf, #01796f, #000000, #feb300\n}}\n\n== Branding and identity ==\nThe Tyne and Wear Metro has a distinctive [[design]] and [[corporate identity]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/metro_design_guide|title=Metro Design Guide - a Freedom of Information request to Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive|date=2018-04-18|website=WhatDoTheyKnow|language=en|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> initially developed to distinguish itself from the antiquated rail system it replaced in the 1980s, as well as to match the livery of the buses operated by the Tyne and Wear Passenger Transport Executive, prior to [[Bus deregulation in Great Britain|deregulation]] in 1986. The ''Calvert'' [[typeface]] was designed specifically for Metro by [[Margaret Calvert]], and is used extensively throughout the system, including on the distinctive black ''M'' logo on a yellow background. The logo is used to denote the Metro, and is featured on cube signs at station entrances, as well as on board trains, and on station signage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/history/how-tyne-wear-metro-made-12031209|title=How the Tyne and Wear Metro was made \u2013 we go back 36 years to the very beginning|last=Meechan|first=Simon|date=16 October 2016|website=ChronicleLive|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the branding identity of the Metro became inconsistent and confused in the late 1990s and early 2000s, Nexus employed a local design agency, Gardiner Richardson, to help the organisation to revive the brand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.designweek.co.uk/issues/may-2009-online/gardiner-richardson-rebrands-tyne-and-wear-metro/|title=Gardiner Richardson rebrands Tyne and Wear Metro|last=|first=|date=2009-05-20|website=Design Week|language=en-UK|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> In 2009, as part of the ''Metro: All Change'' programme, re-branding began to take place. Re-branding saw an emphasis placed on the ''Calvert'' typeface on lettering, signage and maps. It also saw the introduction of a simplified colour scheme of black, white, grey and yellow, to be used on refurbished stations, signage and trains. In 2009, [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]] was the first station to be refurbished, using the new corporate branding and colour scheme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thebeautyoftransport.com/2017/04/19/m-is-for-metro-calvert-typeface-and-the-nexus-tyne-and-wear-public-transport-visual-identity/|title=M is for... Metro (Calvert Typeface and the Nexus Tyne and Wear Public Transport Visual Identity)|last=|first=|date=19 April 2017|website=The Beauty of Transport|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/news/item/nexus-invest-%C2%A340m-metro-modernisation-over-next-12-months|title=Nexus to invest \u00a340m in Metro modernisation over the next 12 months|last=|first=|date=17 June 2015|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Branding and signage\n|width=215 |height=165\n|align=center\n|1=Newcastle Metro sign.jpg|2=The Metro cube sign \u2013 a common sight at stations across the Metro network.|3=Haymarket Metro station, 20 September 2010 (5).jpg|4=A platform at [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], branded in the new corporate colour scheme.|5=Haymarket Metro station, 20 September 2010 (6).jpg|6=Station signage at [[Haymarket Metro station|Haymarket]], branded in the new corporate colour scheme.|7=Jesmond Metro station, 10 April 2010 (1).jpg|8=A platform at [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], branded in the original corporate colour scheme.|9=Jesmond Metro station, 20 September 2010.jpg|10=Station signage at [[Jesmond Metro station|Jesmond]], branded in the original corporate colour scheme.}}\n\n== Art ==\n\nThere are more than 30 pieces of permanent art across the transport network in Tyne and Wear. A number of Metro stations feature commissioned works by various artists, including:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport|title=Art on transport|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n*'''Haymarket:''' ''Canon'' (2010) by Lothar Goetz<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/canon-lothar-goetz|title='Canon' by Lothar Goetz|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*'''Jarrow:''' ''Jarrow March'' (1984) by Vince Rea<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/jarrow-march-vince-rea|title='Jarrow March' by Vince Rea|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*'''Monkseaton:''' ''Beach and Shipyards'' (1983) by Mike Davies<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/beach-shipyards-mike-davies|title='Beach & Shipyards' by Mike Davies|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''Monument:''' ''Parson's Polygon'' (1985) by David Hamilton<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/parsons-polygon-david-hamilton|title='Parsons Polygon' by David Hamilton|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''Queen Elizabeth II Bridge:''' ''Nocturne'' (2007) by Nayan Kulkarni<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/nocturne-nayan-kulkarni|title='Nocturne' by Nayan Kulkarni|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*'''Sunderland:''' ''Platform 5'' (2011) by Jason Bruges Studio<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/platform-5-jason-bruges-studio|title='Platform 5' by Jason Bruges Studio|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jasonbruges.com/platform-5|title=Platform 5|website=Jason Bruges Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*'''Wallsend:''' ''Pontis'' (2003) by Michael Pinsky<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nexus.org.uk/art-transport/commissions/pontis-michael-pinsky|title='Pontis' by Michael Pinsky|last=|first=|date=|website=Nexus|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n{{Gallery\n|title=Art\n|width=215 |height=165\n|align=center\n|footer=\n|Haymarket Metro station, 20 September 2010 (8).jpg|alt1=\n |Canon (2010)|Parsons Polygon, Blackett Street (geograph 1697679).jpg|alt2=\n |Parson's Polygon (1985)|Hadrian's Wall - Tyne and Wear Metro style.jpg|alt3= \n |Pontis (2003)}}\n==Proposed future upgrades and development==\n===Extension to Washington IAMP===\nThere have been a number of proposals looking in to the possibility of re-opening the former [[Leamside line|Leamside Line]] to [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]], including a 2009 report from the [[Association of train operating companies|Association of Train Operating Companies (ATOC)]],{{ATOCConnectingCommunitiesReportS10}} and a 2016 proposal from the [[North East Combined Authority|North East Combined Authority (NECA)]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://northeastca.gov.uk/news/neca-sets-out-bold-ambitions-metro-and-local-rail-services/|title=NECA sets out bold ambitions for Metro and local rail services|date=2016-07-19|website=North East Combined Authority|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> as well as the abandoned ''Project Orpheus'' programme, from the early 2000s. Most recently, proposals are being put forward to link the current network at [[Pelaw Metro station|Pelaw]] and [[South Hylton Metro station|South Hylton]], with the International Advanced Manufacturing Park in [[Washington, Tyne and Wear|Washington]], using part of the alignment of the former [[Leamside line|Leamside Line]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/hopes-metro-could-extended-business-15652152|title=Hopes Metro could be extended to business park near Sunderland's Nissan plant|last=Harrison|first=James|date=2019-01-10|website=ChronicleLive|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shieldsgazette.com/news/politics/council/detailed-talks-underway-extend-metro-south-tyneside-and-sunderland-serve-iamp-2503956|title='Detailed talks' underway to extend Metro to serve giant new business park|last=Harrison|first=James|date=22 March 2020|website=The Shields Gazette|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Durham Coast Line]]\n* [[Leamside line|Leamside Line]]\n* [[List of Tyne and Wear Metro stations]]\n* [[North Tyneside Loop]]\n* [[South Gosforth TMD]]\n* [[Transport in Tyne and Wear]]\n* [[Tyne & Wear Metrocars|Tyne and Wear Metrocars]]\n* [[Tyneside Electrics]]\n* [[Urban rail in the United Kingdom]]\n\n== References ==\n{{clear}}\n{